{"title_page": "Boyz in the Sink", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Boyz in the Sink\n| image =\n| caption =\n| image_size =\n| background =group_or_band\n| origin = ''VeggieTales''\n| genre = Christian pop\n| years_active = 2003\u20132007, 2012\n| label = [[Big Idea Entertainment]], Bob and Larry Records\n| associated_acts =\n| website =\n| current_members = Larry the Cucumber<br>Junior Asparagus<br>Jimmy Gourd<br>Mr. Lunt\n}}\n\n'''Boyz in the Sink''' is a fictional band of ''[[VeggieTales]]'' characters who first appeared in the 2003 [[Silly Songs with Larry]] segment of ''[[The Ballad of Little Joe]].'' The band has subsequently appeared in 2007's [[Moe and the Big Exit]] <ref>{{cite news|title=VeggieTales Latest Blends Bonanza and Bible|last=Blakey|first=Scott|work=[[South Florida Sun-Sentinel]]|date=2004-01-30|page=12|id={{ProQuest|387821280}}}} (Registration required)</ref> and 2012's ''If I Sang A Silly Song'' and ''[[Robin Good and The Not-So-Merry Men]].''\n\nLike other recurring themes such as [[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie|The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything]], the group is made up of familiar VeggieTales characters performing specific roles. The members of the band are [[Larry the Cucumber]], [[Mr. Lunt]], [[Junior Asparagus]], and [[Jimmy Gourd]]. The foursome and their name are parodies of \"boy-bands\" including [[Boyz n the Hood]]<ref name=owh>{{cite news|title=Veggies are Good for Co-Creator Mike Nawrocki|last=Keenan|first=John|work=[[Omaha World-Herald]]|date=2005-07-05|page=01E|id={{ProQuest|400636803}}}} (Registration required)</ref> and the [[Backstreet Boys]].\n\n== Songs ==\n\n===Bellybutton===\n\"Belly Button\", their first song, is Lunt's musical lament that he lacks a navel depicted through his visit to a medical clinic. [[Tim Hodge]] voices Khalil the Caterpillar, who appears dressed as a physician who informs Lunt that his stem serves the purpose as a belly button. While originally included as the Silly Song for ''The Ballad of Little Joe'', the video was released separately and won the Children's Jury Award for Animated Short Film or Video at the 2004 [[Chicago International Children's Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=21st Annual Chicago International Children'S Film Festival 2004 Awards|url=http://www.cicff.org/bin/file/docs/Award%20List%202004.pdf|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=[[Chicago International Children's Film Festival]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412161607/http://www.cicff.org/bin/file/docs/Award%20List%202004.pdf|archive-date=12 April 2016}}</ref> The song has been cited as the favorite silly song of VeggieTales co-creator and voice of Larry [[Mike Nawrocki]]<ref name=owh /> and [[Milwaukee Bucks]] center [[Jake Voskuhl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bucks/features/questions_5th_grader.html|title=Truman Reed's Questions from a Fifth Grader|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref>\n\n===A Mess Down in Egypt===\nFor the silly song in the VeggieTales episode ''Moe and the Big Exit'', the group interrupts the silly song announcer in order to tell the Moses story their own way, with a rap entitled \"A Mess Down in Egypt\". As you know, Mr. Lunt in the dark blue shirt leads this song too. This is the 2nd one in a row Mr. Lunt sang.<ref>{{cite web|title=Moe & The Big Exit Veggietales DVD|url=https://bigidea.com/products/shows/shows_content.aspx?pid=139|accessdate=2009-08-24|publisher=[[Big Idea Entertainment|Big Idea]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103134228/https://bigidea.com/products/shows/shows_content.aspx?pid=139|archivedate=2010-01-03}}</ref> The movie website, [[Rotten Tomatoes]], called the silly song a \"charmingly goofy musical number\".<ref>{{cite web|title=VeggieTales - Moe and the Big Exit (2007)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/veggietales_moe_and_the_big_exit/?critic=3#contentReviews|date=2007-11-01|accessdate=2009-08-24|last=Angulo Chen|first=Sandie|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref>\n\n===Bubble Rap===\nThe song appears on the ''Silly Song'' compilation video, ''If I Sang A Silly Song'' as the band, again joined by Khalil, sings of the wonders of the packing material\n\n===Other Songs===\n* \"You Put This Love In My Heart\" appears on the album ''Veggietales Worship Songs'' and was originally recorded and sung by Boyz in the Sink.\n* \"Jesus Is Just Alright\" appears on the album ''Bob and Larry Sing the 70's'' and is a cover of Boyz in the Sink hit.\n* \"Christmas Sizzle Boy\" appears on the album ''The Incredible Singing Christmas Tree''.\n* \"Easter Bunny Hop\" appears on the album ''A Very Veggie Easter''.\n\n==First album==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Boyz in the Sink\n| type       = live\n| artist     = Boyz in the Sink\n| cover      =\n| alt        = \"Boys in the Sink\" first album cover, depicting the animated band members\n| released   = 2006\n| recorded   = 2003-2006\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Boy band]], [[Children's music]]\n| length     = 0:42:51\n| label      = [[EMI]], [[Big Idea Productions|Big Idea]]\n| producer   = [[Mike Nawrocki]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe band's only album series, ''Boyz in the Sink'', was released by [[EMI]] and [[Big Idea Productions]] on October 3, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boyz in the Sink VeggieTales CD|url=https://bigidea.com/products/music/music_content.aspx?pid=80|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=[[Big Idea Entertainment|Big Idea]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103152353/https://bigidea.com/products/music/music_content.aspx?pid=80|archivedate=2010-01-03}}</ref> It peaked in 2007 at #10 on the Billboard Top Kid Audio chart<ref>{{cite web|title=VeggieTales|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p390556/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=Allmusic.com}}</ref> and features many covers of songs from ''VeggieTales''.\n=== Track listing of album 1===\n# Boyz in the Sink - 2:35\n# Bigger Than The Boogie Man ([[Where's God When I'm S-Scared?]]) - 3:43\n# The B-O-Y-Z Dance (featuring [[Kirk Franklin]] as himself) - 2:43\n# Belly Button 2006 ([[The Ballad of Little Joe]]; featuring Kirk Franklin as himself) - 3:30\n# The Hairbrush Song ([[Are You My Neighbor?]]) - 2:31\n# Do the Moo Shoo ([[The Ultimate Silly Song Countdown]]) - 1:00\n# My Day (Junior's Bedtime Songs) - 4:03\n# The Funky Polka - 3:13\n# Cheeseburger ([[Madame Blueberry]]) - 3:10\n# Oh No! What We Gonna Do? ([[Where's God When I'm S-Scared?]]) - 2:08\n# I Can Be Your Friend ([[Are You My Neighbor?]]) - 3:21\n\n==Other Media==\nBig Idea released a jigsaw puzzle featuring Boyz in the Sink.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigidea.com/products/toys/toys_content.aspx?pid=335|title=Boyz in he Sink VeggieTales Inlaid Puzzle|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=[[Big Idea Entertainment|Big Idea]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206103432/https://bigidea.com/products/toys/toys_content.aspx?pid=335|archivedate=2010-02-06}}</ref> Boyz in the Sink also appear on the 2006 Big Idea release ''Veggie Tales: Worship Songs''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Religious Music|last=Castillo|first=Brent|work=[[The Wichita Eagle]] via McClatchey Tribune News Service|date=2006-03-29|id={{ProQuest|456562983}}}} (Registration required)</ref> The band was featured as part of 2005's \"VeggieTales Rockin' Tour LIVE\",<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Christian Post]]|title=VeggieTales Rockin' Tour LIVE! Hits The Road This Summer|last=Camacho|first=Justin|date=2005-04-26|accessdate=2009-07-20|url=http://www.christianpost.com/article/20050426/veggietales-rockin-tour-live-hits-the-road-this-summer/index.html}}</ref> the second traveling stage show featuring VeggieTales music and characters.<ref>{{cite news|last=Neal|first=Robert|work=[[Tulsa World]]|title=Lettuce Entertain You|date=2005-08-15|issn=8750-5959|id={{ProQuest|399992969}}}} (Registration required)</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://us.imdb.com/title/tt0439132/ Bellybutton] at [[IMDB.com]]\n* [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r858526|pure_url=yes}} Boyz in the Sink] at [[Allmusic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{VeggieTales}}\n\n[[Category:VeggieTales]]\n[[Category:Fictional musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Boyz in the Sink\n| image =\n| caption =\n| image_size =\n| background =group_or_band\n| origin = ''VeggieTales''\n| genre = Christian pop\n| years_active = 2003\u20132007, 2012\n| label = [[Big Idea Entertainment]], Bob and Larry Records\n| associated_acts =\n| website =\n| current_members = Larry the Cucumber<br>Junior Asparagus<br>Jimmy Gourd<br>Mr. Lunt\n}}\n\n'''Boyz in the Sink''' is a fictional band of ''[[VeggieTales]]'' characters who first appeared in the 2003 [[Silly Songs with Larry]] segment of ''[[The Ballad of Little Joe]].'' The band has subsequently appeared in 2007's [[Moe and the Big Exit]] <ref>{{cite news|title=VeggieTales Latest Blends Bonanza and Bible|last=Blakey|first=Scott|work=[[South Florida Sun-Sentinel]]|date=2004-01-30|page=12|id={{ProQuest|387821280}}}} (Registration required)</ref> and 2012's ''If I Sang A Silly Song'' and ''[[Robin Good and The Not-So-Merry Men]].''\n\nLike other recurring themes such as [[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie|The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything]], the group is made up of familiar VeggieTales characters performing specific roles. The members of the band are [[Larry the Cucumber]], [[Mr. Lunt]], [[Junior Asparagus]], and [[Jimmy Gourd]]. The foursome and their name are parodies of \"boy-bands\" including [[NSYNC]]<ref name=owh>{{cite news|title=Veggies are Good for Co-Creator Mike Nawrocki|last=Keenan|first=John|work=[[Omaha World-Herald]]|date=2005-07-05|page=01E|id={{ProQuest|400636803}}}} (Registration required)</ref> and the [[Backstreet Boys]].\n\n== Songs ==\n\n===Bellybutton===\n\"Belly Button\", their first song, is Lunt's musical lament that he lacks a navel depicted through his visit to a medical clinic. [[Tim Hodge]] voices Khalil the Caterpillar, who appears dressed as a physician who informs Lunt that his stem serves the purpose as a belly button. While originally included as the Silly Song for ''The Ballad of Little Joe'', the video was released separately and won the Children's Jury Award for Animated Short Film or Video at the 2004 [[Chicago International Children's Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=21st Annual Chicago International Children'S Film Festival 2004 Awards|url=http://www.cicff.org/bin/file/docs/Award%20List%202004.pdf|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=[[Chicago International Children's Film Festival]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412161607/http://www.cicff.org/bin/file/docs/Award%20List%202004.pdf|archive-date=12 April 2016}}</ref> The song has been cited as the favorite silly song of VeggieTales co-creator and voice of Larry [[Mike Nawrocki]]<ref name=owh /> and [[Milwaukee Bucks]] center [[Jake Voskuhl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bucks/features/questions_5th_grader.html|title=Truman Reed's Questions from a Fifth Grader|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref>\n\n===A Mess Down in Egypt===\nFor the silly song in the VeggieTales episode ''Moe and the Big Exit'', the group interrupts the silly song announcer in order to tell the Moses story their own way, with a rap entitled \"A Mess Down in Egypt\". As you know, Mr. Lunt in the dark blue shirt leads this song too. This is the 2nd one in a row Mr. Lunt sang.<ref>{{cite web|title=Moe & The Big Exit Veggietales DVD|url=https://bigidea.com/products/shows/shows_content.aspx?pid=139|accessdate=2009-08-24|publisher=[[Big Idea Entertainment|Big Idea]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103134228/https://bigidea.com/products/shows/shows_content.aspx?pid=139|archivedate=2010-01-03}}</ref> The movie website, [[Rotten Tomatoes]], called the silly song a \"charmingly goofy musical number\".<ref>{{cite web|title=VeggieTales - Moe and the Big Exit (2007)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/veggietales_moe_and_the_big_exit/?critic=3#contentReviews|date=2007-11-01|accessdate=2009-08-24|last=Angulo Chen|first=Sandie|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref>\n\n===Bubble Rap===\nThe song appears on the ''Silly Song'' compilation video, ''If I Sang A Silly Song'' as the band, again joined by Khalil, sings of the wonders of the packing material\n\n===Other Songs===\n* \"You Put This Love In My Heart\" appears on the album ''Veggietales Worship Songs'' and was originally recorded and sung by Boyz in the Sink.\n* \"Jesus Is Just Alright\" appears on the album ''Bob and Larry Sing the 70's'' and is a cover of Boyz in the Sink hit.\n* \"Christmas Sizzle Boy\" appears on the album ''The Incredible Singing Christmas Tree''.\n* \"Easter Bunny Hop\" appears on the album ''A Very Veggie Easter''.\n\n==First album==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Boyz in the Sink\n| type       = live\n| artist     = Boyz in the Sink\n| cover      =\n| alt        = \"Boys in the Sink\" first album cover, depicting the animated band members\n| released   = 2006\n| recorded   = 2003-2006\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Boy band]], [[Children's music]]\n| length     = 0:42:51\n| label      = [[EMI]], [[Big Idea Productions|Big Idea]]\n| producer   = [[Mike Nawrocki]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe band's only album series, ''Boyz in the Sink'', was released by [[EMI]] and [[Big Idea Productions]] on October 3, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boyz in the Sink VeggieTales CD|url=https://bigidea.com/products/music/music_content.aspx?pid=80|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=[[Big Idea Entertainment|Big Idea]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103152353/https://bigidea.com/products/music/music_content.aspx?pid=80|archivedate=2010-01-03}}</ref> It peaked in 2007 at #10 on the Billboard Top Kid Audio chart<ref>{{cite web|title=VeggieTales|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p390556/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=Allmusic.com}}</ref> and features many covers of songs from ''VeggieTales''.\n=== Track listing of album 1===\n# Boyz in the Sink - 2:35\n# Bigger Than The Boogie Man ([[Where's God When I'm S-Scared?]]) - 3:43\n# The B-O-Y-Z Dance (featuring [[Kirk Franklin]] as himself) - 2:43\n# Belly Button 2006 ([[The Ballad of Little Joe]]; featuring Kirk Franklin as himself) - 3:30\n# The Hairbrush Song ([[Are You My Neighbor?]]) - 2:31\n# Do the Moo Shoo ([[The Ultimate Silly Song Countdown]]) - 1:00\n# My Day (Junior's Bedtime Songs) - 4:03\n# The Funky Polka - 3:13\n# Cheeseburger ([[Madame Blueberry]]) - 3:10\n# Oh No! What We Gonna Do? ([[Where's God When I'm S-Scared?]]) - 2:08\n# I Can Be Your Friend ([[Are You My Neighbor?]]) - 3:21\n\n==Other Media==\nBig Idea released a jigsaw puzzle featuring Boyz in the Sink.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigidea.com/products/toys/toys_content.aspx?pid=335|title=Boyz in he Sink VeggieTales Inlaid Puzzle|accessdate=2009-07-20|publisher=[[Big Idea Entertainment|Big Idea]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206103432/https://bigidea.com/products/toys/toys_content.aspx?pid=335|archivedate=2010-02-06}}</ref> Boyz in the Sink also appear on the 2006 Big Idea release ''Veggie Tales: Worship Songs''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Religious Music|last=Castillo|first=Brent|work=[[The Wichita Eagle]] via McClatchey Tribune News Service|date=2006-03-29|id={{ProQuest|456562983}}}} (Registration required)</ref> The band was featured as part of 2005's \"VeggieTales Rockin' Tour LIVE\",<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Christian Post]]|title=VeggieTales Rockin' Tour LIVE! Hits The Road This Summer|last=Camacho|first=Justin|date=2005-04-26|accessdate=2009-07-20|url=http://www.christianpost.com/article/20050426/veggietales-rockin-tour-live-hits-the-road-this-summer/index.html}}</ref> the second traveling stage show featuring VeggieTales music and characters.<ref>{{cite news|last=Neal|first=Robert|work=[[Tulsa World]]|title=Lettuce Entertain You|date=2005-08-15|issn=8750-5959|id={{ProQuest|399992969}}}} (Registration required)</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://us.imdb.com/title/tt0439132/ Bellybutton] at [[IMDB.com]]\n* [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r858526|pure_url=yes}} Boyz in the Sink] at [[Allmusic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{VeggieTales}}\n\n[[Category:VeggieTales]]\n[[Category:Fictional musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "Materialscientist", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Reverted edits by2600:1700:C970:34F0:15DA:D1EB:C2A2:9C90(talk): not providing areliable source(WP:CITE,WP:RS) (HG) (3.4.10))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boyz_in_the_Sink"}
{"title_page": "Now You See It...", "text_new": "{{About|the 2005 Disney telefilm|the Mark Goodson-Bill Todman game show|Now You See It (U.S. game show)|the 2013 film|Now You See Me (film)|other uses|Now You See It (disambiguation)}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Unreferenced|date=November 2008}}\n{{Original research|date=November 2008}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Now You See It....\n| image                = Now You See It.jpg\n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Promotional poster\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = Bill Fritz\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Duwayne Dunham]]\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Aly Michalka]]\n* [[Johnny Pacar]]\n}}\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Phil Marshall\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = Jacqueline George\n| editor               = \n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 83 minutes\n| company              = [[J. Rupert Thompson|Evolution Film & Tape]]<br>[[Disney Channel|Disney Channel Original Productions]]\n| distributor          = [[Buena Vista Television]]\n\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[Disney Channel]]\n| first_aired          = {{Film date|TV=y|2005|1|14}}\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Now You See It...''''' is a 2005 [[Disney Channel Original Movie]]. The film is told from Allyson's ([[Aly Michalka]]) point of view, similar to a documentary and tells the story of what can happen when a reality TV show uncovers something that is not meant to be seen on television.\n\n==Plot==\n{{plot|date=September 2018}}\nAspiring teen producer Allyson Miller ([[Alyson Michalka]]) signs up to produce a new reality show, searching for the world's greatest kid magician. Desperate to find her star, Allyson (along with adult mentor Paul, and kid cameraman Cedric) stumbles upon Danny Sinclair ([[Johnny Pacar]]), who gets them on the show. When Danny is selected as one of three finalists, he appears to have something more than the others. Even show host and master magician Max ([[Frank Langella]]) takes a special interest in Danny's talent. \n\nWhen Danny confesses to Allyson that his powers are real, she is shocked but promises to believe him. She feels they have something in common since they have both never had friends. Unfortunately, after an interrogation by Max and a panel of experts, Danny is apparently proven to be a fake. Betrayed, Allyson refuses to talk to Danny. However, when she views the first video of him, she sees doves appear from nowhere and begins to believe in him again. When she goes to look for him, she hears voices through a door and eavesdrops on the conversation.\n\nShe finds that Max is confessing to Danny that he, too, is a real magician \u2014 a sorcerer. After Max demonstrates his talents, he promises to help Danny control his powers and gives him a ring. He tells Danny that whenever he wears the ring, Danny will be fully in control of his own powers. Danny puts it on and leaves the room. Paul enters, and Max reveals his plan: to control Danny's powers through the ring, and whenever Danny wears it, he will slowly lose his powers.\n\nAllyson rushes to try to find Danny, but he already trusts Max too much. When Allyson tries to show the tape to the show's producer, Max uses his powers to erase it. The producer asks her to leave, believing she has cracked under the pressure. Allyson leaves, upset because Danny did not stand up for her. On the train home, she remembers the famous magician Antonio DeMilo, whom Max called his 'mentor.' When she researches this, she discovers that DeMilo died when a prop collapsed on him. He was wearing the ring Danny is wearing now, and Allyson realizes Danny is in grave danger.\n\nAllyson manages to re-enter the grand finale of the show inside a magic 'box'. She warns Danny again, telling him that he can't remove the ring alone, he needs someone to remove it for him. Danny goes on-stage, where Max tries to make a 1000&nbsp;lb weight collapse on him, but Allyson's warning helps him escape. Danny and Max are then locked in combat; the audience thinks it is all part of the show. After a fight, Allyson is able to remove the ring from Danny, who then places it onto Max - he disappears. Allyson and Danny bow, and Danny kisses Allyson's hand.\n\nAt the end of the movie, Allyson speaks into the camera to clarify the events that followed. She believes Paul removed Max's ring after the show, because the tapes soon disappeared. She then reappeared in her room. She says Danny has gone into hiding to learn more about his powers, and prepare for a future showdown with Max, and she doesn't know where he is. Then a popcorn bowl levitates from behind her and comes to her arms. She laughs and says that she does know. She is then teleported next to Danny, who seems in much better control of his powers. They laugh as she sits next to him with his arm around her shoulder, thus hinting at a romantic attachment.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Aly Michalka]] as Allyson Miller\n* [[Johnny Pacar]] as Danny Sinclair\n* [[Frank Langella]] as Max\n*Dremaceo Giles as Ron\n*Patrick Hazell as Mr. Sinclair\n* Brendan Hill as Cedric\n* [[Chris Olivero]] as Hunter\n*Andrea Ragsdale as Mrs. Sinclair\n* [[Amanda Shaw]] as Zoey Cunningham\n*[[Gabriel Sunday]] as Brandon\n*Deneen Tyler as Ms. McCallister\n* [[Spike Spencer]] as Paul\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0426568}}\n\n{{Disney Channel Original Movies}}\n{{Duwayne Dunham}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Now You See It}}\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:Disney Channel Original Movie films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Orleans]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2005 television films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Duwayne Dunham]]\n[[Category:Films about magic and magicians]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Orleans]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 2005 Disney telefilm|the Mark Goodson-Bill Todman game show|Now You See It (U.S. game show)|the 2013 film|Now You See Me (film)|other uses|Now You See It (disambiguation)}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Unreferenced|date=November 2008}}\n{{Original research|date=November 2008}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Now You See It....\n| image                = Now You See It.jpg\n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Promotional poster\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = Bill Fritz\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Duwayne Dunham]]\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Aly Michalka]]\n* [[Johnny Pacar]]\n}}\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Phil Marshall\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = Jacqueline George\n| editor               = \n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 83 minutes\n| company              = [[J. Rupert Thompson|Evolution Film & Tape]]\n| distributor          = [[Buena Vista Television]]\n\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[Disney Channel]]\n| first_aired          = {{Film date|TV=y|2005|1|14}}\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Now You See It...''''' is a 2005 [[Disney Channel Original Movie]]. The film is told from Allyson's ([[Aly Michalka]]) point of view, similar to a documentary and tells the story of what can happen when a reality TV show uncovers something that is not meant to be seen on television. \n\n==Plot==\n{{plot|date=September 2018}}\nAspiring teen producer Allyson Miller ([[Alyson Michalka]]) signs up to produce a new reality show, searching for the world's greatest kid magician. Desperate to find her star, Allyson (along with adult mentor Paul, and kid cameraman Cedric) stumbles upon Danny Sinclair ([[Johnny Pacar]]), who gets them on the show. When Danny is selected as one of three finalists, he appears to have something more than the others. Even show host and master magician Max ([[Frank Langella]]) takes a special interest in Danny's talent. \n\nWhen Danny confesses to Allyson that his powers are real, she is shocked but promises to believe him. She feels they have something in common since they have both never had friends. Unfortunately, after an interrogation by Max and a panel of experts, Danny is apparently proven to be a fake. Betrayed, Allyson refuses to talk to Danny. However, when she views the first video of him, she sees doves appear from nowhere and begins to believe in him again. When she goes to look for him, she hears voices through a door and eavesdrops on the conversation.\n\nShe finds that Max is confessing to Danny that he, too, is a real magician \u2014 a sorcerer. After Max demonstrates his talents, he promises to help Danny control his powers and gives him a ring. He tells Danny that whenever he wears the ring, Danny will be fully in control of his own powers. Danny puts it on and leaves the room. Paul enters, and Max reveals his plan: to control Danny's powers through the ring, and whenever Danny wears it, he will slowly lose his powers.\n\nAllyson rushes to try to find Danny, but he already trusts Max too much. When Allyson tries to show the tape to the show's producer, Max uses his powers to erase it. The producer asks her to leave, believing she has cracked under the pressure. Allyson leaves, upset because Danny did not stand up for her. On the train home, she remembers the famous magician Antonio DeMilo, whom Max called his 'mentor.' When she researches this, she discovers that DeMilo died when a prop collapsed on him. He was wearing the ring Danny is wearing now, and Allyson realizes Danny is in grave danger.\n\nAllyson manages to re-enter the grand finale of the show inside a magic 'box'. She warns Danny again, telling him that he can't remove the ring alone, he needs someone to remove it for him. Danny goes on-stage, where Max tries to make a 1000&nbsp;lb weight collapse on him, but Allyson's warning helps him escape. Danny and Max are then locked in combat; the audience thinks it is all part of the show. After a fight, Allyson is able to remove the ring from Danny, who then places it onto Max - he disappears. Allyson and Danny bow, and Danny kisses Allyson's hand.\n\nAt the end of the movie, Allyson speaks into the camera to clarify the events that followed. She believes Paul removed Max's ring after the show, because the tapes soon disappeared. She then reappeared in her room. She says Danny has gone into hiding to learn more about his powers, and prepare for a future showdown with Max, and she doesn't know where he is. Then a popcorn bowl levitates from behind her and comes to her arms. She laughs and says that she does know. She is then teleported next to Danny, who seems in much better control of his powers. They laugh as she sits next to him with his arm around her shoulder, thus hinting at a romantic attachment.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Aly Michalka]] as Allyson Miller\n* [[Johnny Pacar]] as Danny Sinclair\n* [[Frank Langella]] as Max\n*Dremaceo Giles as Ron\n*Patrick Hazell as Mr. Sinclair\n* Brendan Hill as Cedric\n* [[Chris Olivero]] as Hunter\n*Andrea Ragsdale as Mrs. Sinclair\n* [[Amanda Shaw]] as Zoey Cunningham\n*[[Gabriel Sunday]] as Brandon\n*Deneen Tyler as Ms. McCallister\n* [[Spike Spencer]] as Paul\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0426568}}\n\n{{Disney Channel Original Movies}}\n{{Duwayne Dunham}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Now You See It}}\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:Disney Channel Original Movie films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Orleans]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2005 television films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Duwayne Dunham]]\n[[Category:Films about magic and magicians]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Orleans]]\n", "name_user": "174.250.144.205", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Now_You_See_It..."}
{"title_page": "Porochista Khakpour", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Porochista Khakpour\n| image = Porochista khakpour 2014.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Khakpour at the 2014 Texas Book Festival\n| birth_name = Porochista Khakpour\n| alma_mater = [[Sarah Lawrence College]] [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|1|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Tehran, Iran]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = [[Novelist]], [[Essayist]]\n| genre = [[Literary fiction]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.porochistakhakpour.com/}}\n}}\n'''Porochista Khakpour''' (born 1978) is an [[Iranian American]] novelist and writer. She is racist and had an issue in March 2020 with the fandom from BTS. Telling lies that the fandom was racist just because she got called out saying the n-word and doing the blackface on instagram. Her excuse was that it was a \"potatoe face\" even tho the filter was the \"Doll me Up\" Filter. The thing is it isn't the first time she is doing it. She got mad and started to bring BTS past and started to insult them. Not how she started to insult the fandom. She is manipulative and she played the victim and faked some chats to prove her point. That's pathetic. This woman is sick. On reddit are all evidence what she did before. She is not very loveable.\n\nLinks are here for the evidence:\n\n<nowiki>https://www.reddit.com/r/illnessfakersgonewild/comments/eadnm6/lets_watch_porochista_khakpour_destroy_her_own/</nowiki> \n\n\nhttps://www.reddit.com/r/illnessfakersgonewild/comments/ffc9p5/the_porochista_khakpour_megathread_comment/\n\n(I know it will get deleted because she can't handle the truth. Poor grown little sick woman. :/) \n\n\n\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]], Khakpour was raised in [[South Pasadena, California]] and the Los Angeles area, graduating from [[South Pasadena High School]]. Khakpour attended [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in [[New York (state)|New York]] for her BA, majoring in Creative Writing and Literature. She received her MA from [[Johns Hopkins University]] and the [[Johns Hopkins Writing Seminars]]. After receiving her MA, she was a Lecturer and an [[Eliot Coleman]] fellow at [[Johns Hopkins University]].\n\n==Career ==\nHer first novel, ''Sons and Other Flammable Objects'' was published in September 2007. Khakpour's second novel, ''The Last Illusion'', was released on May 13, 2014.\n\nKhakpour has taught at [[Hofstra University]] as an Adjunct Professor and at the [[College of Santa Fe]]. She was also a Visiting Assistant Professor at [[Bucknell University]], and the Picador Guest Professor of Literature at the [[University of Leipzig]] in [[Leipzig, Germany]]. She has also been a Visiting Writer at [[Wesleyan University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wesleyan.edu/writing/creativewriting.html|title=Writing Workshop, Writing at Wesleyan - Wesleyan University|website=www.wesleyan.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref> and [[Northwestern University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mena.northwestern.edu/documents/porochista-khakpour-coming-to-northwestern-as-visiting-writer-in-residence.html|title=Upcoming Events with Visiting Writer-in-Residence Porochista Khakpour: Middle East and North African Studies Program - Northwestern University|website=www.mena.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she published ''Sick'', a \"memoir of chronic illness, misdiagnosis, addiction, and the myth of full recovery.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://porochistakhakpour.com/books/sick/|title=Sick - Porochista Khakpour.com|work=Porochista Khakpour.com|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref> ''The Week'' magazine selected the memoir as 'Book of the week' in June, 2018. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/the-week-us/20180622/282076277577216|title=PressReader.com - Your favorite newspapers and magazines.|website=www.pressreader.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she published  ''Parsnips in Love'', a critically acclaimed soft erotica novel. \n\nIn May 2020, [[Penguin Random House]] will publish Brown Album, a collection of essays, \"chronicling immigrant and Iranian-American life in our contemporary moment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/598265/brown-album-by-porochista-khakpour/|title=Brown Album by Porochista Khakpour: 9780525564713 &#124; PenguinRandomHouse.com: Books|website=PenguinRandomhouse.com}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and accolades==\nKhakpour is a recipient of the 2012 [[National Endowment for the Arts]] (NEA) Literature Fellowship in Creative Writing (Prose). Khakpour has also received fellowships from the [[Sewanee Writers' Conference]], [[Northwestern University]], the [[Virginia Center for the Creative Arts]], The Ucross Foundation, Yaddo and Djerassi.<ref>Porochista Khakpour, Biography, http://porochistakhakpour.com/biography/</ref> Her work has also been nominated for a [[Pushcart Prize]].<ref>Porochista Khakpour, Los Angeles Review of Books, {{cite web |url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/author/porochista-khakpour |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220235630/https://lareviewofbooks.org/author/porochista-khakpour |archivedate=2013-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nKhakpour's first novel, ''Sons and Other Flammable Objects'' (Grove/Atlantic 2007) also won the 77th annual [[California Book Award]] \"First Fiction\" prize. The novel was also a ''[[New York Times]]'' Editor's Choice and included on the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'''s 2007 \"Fall's Best\" list. The novel was also shortlisted for the [[William Saroyan International Prize for Writing]], and longlisted for the 2008 [[Dylan Thomas Prize]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sampsoniaway.org/literary-voices/2017/06/30/i-will-raise-my-hand-and-be-heard-an-interview-with-porochista-khakpour/|title=I Will Raise My Hand and Be Heard: An Interview With Porochista Khakpour {{!}} Sampsonia Way Magazine|website=www.sampsoniaway.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==  Works ==\n* ''Sons and other flammable objects'', New York Grove Press 2007. {{ISBN|9780802118530}}, {{OCLC|836838639}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pages.jh.edu/jhumag/1108web/khakpour.html|title=Johns Hopkins Magazine|website=pages.jh.edu|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n*''The last illusion'', London : Bloomsbury, 2016. {{ISBN|9781408858592}}, {{OCLC|990147921}}\n* ''Sick: a life of lyme, love, illness, and addiction.''  New York: Harper Collins, 2017. {{ISBN|9780062428738}}, {{OCLC|972254441}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/porochista-khakpour/sick-khakpour/|title=SICK by Porochista Khakpour {{!}} Kirkus Reviews|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commonscategory}}\n* [http://www.porochistakhakpour.com/ Khakpour's website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khakpour, Porochista}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Iranian women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Tehran]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:American writers of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Refugees and displaced people in fiction]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Porochista Khakpour\n| image = Porochista khakpour 2014.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Khakpour at the 2014 Texas Book Festival\n| birth_name = Porochista Khakpour\n| alma_mater = [[Sarah Lawrence College]] [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|1|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Tehran, Iran]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = [[Novelist]], [[Essayist]]\n| genre = [[Literary fiction]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.porochistakhakpour.com/}}\n}}\n'''Porochista Khakpour''' (born 1978) is an [[Iranian American]] novelist and writer.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]], Khakpour was raised in [[South Pasadena, California]] and the Los Angeles area, graduating from [[South Pasadena High School]]. Khakpour attended [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in [[New York (state)|New York]] for her BA, majoring in Creative Writing and Literature. She received her MA from [[Johns Hopkins University]] and the [[Johns Hopkins Writing Seminars]]. After receiving her MA, she was a Lecturer and an [[Eliot Coleman]] fellow at [[Johns Hopkins University]].\n\n==Career ==\nHer first novel, ''Sons and Other Flammable Objects'' was published in September 2007. Khakpour's second novel, ''The Last Illusion'', was released on May 13, 2014.\n\nKhakpour has taught at [[Hofstra University]] as an Adjunct Professor and at the [[College of Santa Fe]]. She was also a Visiting Assistant Professor at [[Bucknell University]], and the Picador Guest Professor of Literature at the [[University of Leipzig]] in [[Leipzig, Germany]]. She has also been a Visiting Writer at [[Wesleyan University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wesleyan.edu/writing/creativewriting.html|title=Writing Workshop, Writing at Wesleyan - Wesleyan University|website=www.wesleyan.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref> and [[Northwestern University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mena.northwestern.edu/documents/porochista-khakpour-coming-to-northwestern-as-visiting-writer-in-residence.html|title=Upcoming Events with Visiting Writer-in-Residence Porochista Khakpour: Middle East and North African Studies Program - Northwestern University|website=www.mena.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she published ''Sick'', a \"memoir of chronic illness, misdiagnosis, addiction, and the myth of full recovery.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://porochistakhakpour.com/books/sick/|title=Sick - Porochista Khakpour.com|work=Porochista Khakpour.com|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref> ''The Week'' magazine selected the memoir as 'Book of the week' in June, 2018. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/the-week-us/20180622/282076277577216|title=PressReader.com - Your favorite newspapers and magazines.|website=www.pressreader.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she published  ''Parsnips in Love'', a critically acclaimed soft erotica novel. \n\nIn May 2020, [[Penguin Random House]] will publish Brown Album, a collection of essays, \"chronicling immigrant and Iranian-American life in our contemporary moment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/598265/brown-album-by-porochista-khakpour/|title=Brown Album by Porochista Khakpour: 9780525564713 &#124; PenguinRandomHouse.com: Books|website=PenguinRandomhouse.com}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and accolades==\nKhakpour is a recipient of the 2012 [[National Endowment for the Arts]] (NEA) Literature Fellowship in Creative Writing (Prose). Khakpour has also received fellowships from the [[Sewanee Writers' Conference]], [[Northwestern University]], the [[Virginia Center for the Creative Arts]], The Ucross Foundation, Yaddo and Djerassi.<ref>Porochista Khakpour, Biography, http://porochistakhakpour.com/biography/</ref> Her work has also been nominated for a [[Pushcart Prize]].<ref>Porochista Khakpour, Los Angeles Review of Books, {{cite web |url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/author/porochista-khakpour |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220235630/https://lareviewofbooks.org/author/porochista-khakpour |archivedate=2013-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nKhakpour's first novel, ''Sons and Other Flammable Objects'' (Grove/Atlantic 2007) also won the 77th annual [[California Book Award]] \"First Fiction\" prize. The novel was also a ''[[New York Times]]'' Editor's Choice and included on the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'''s 2007 \"Fall's Best\" list. The novel was also shortlisted for the [[William Saroyan International Prize for Writing]], and longlisted for the 2008 [[Dylan Thomas Prize]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sampsoniaway.org/literary-voices/2017/06/30/i-will-raise-my-hand-and-be-heard-an-interview-with-porochista-khakpour/|title=I Will Raise My Hand and Be Heard: An Interview With Porochista Khakpour {{!}} Sampsonia Way Magazine|website=www.sampsoniaway.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==  Works ==\n* ''Sons and other flammable objects'', New York Grove Press 2007. {{ISBN|9780802118530}}, {{OCLC|836838639}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pages.jh.edu/jhumag/1108web/khakpour.html|title=Johns Hopkins Magazine|website=pages.jh.edu|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n*''The last illusion'', London : Bloomsbury, 2016. {{ISBN|9781408858592}}, {{OCLC|990147921}}\n* ''Sick: a life of lyme, love, illness, and addiction.''  New York: Harper Collins, 2017. {{ISBN|9780062428738}}, {{OCLC|972254441}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/porochista-khakpour/sick-khakpour/|title=SICK by Porochista Khakpour {{!}} Kirkus Reviews|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commonscategory}}\n* [http://www.porochistakhakpour.com/ Khakpour's website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khakpour, Porochista}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Iranian women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Tehran]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:American writers of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Refugees and displaced people in 