{"title_page": "DenizBank", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = DenizBank A.\u015e.\n| logo = DenizBank logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[S.A. (corporation)|Anonim \u015eirket]]\n| traded_as = {{imkb|DENIZ}}\n| foundation = 1938 in [[Istanbul]]\n| predecessor = \n| location = [[\u015ei\u015fli]], [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]\n| locations = 740 branches<br>5,612 [[Automated teller machine|ATMs]]\n| num_locations_year = 2017\n| area_served = [[Turkey]]\n| key_people = Hakan Ate\u015f, [[CEO]]\n| industry = [[Finance and Insurance]]\n| products = [[Commercial banking|Banking]]<br>[[Investment banking]]<br>[[Investment management]]\n| num_employees_year = 2017\n| parent = [[Emirates NBD]]\n| num_employees = 14,136\n| homepage = [http://www.denizbank.com/ www.denizbank.com]\n}}\n\n'''DenizBank A.\u015e.''' is a large private bank in [[Turkey]]. It is currently owned by [[Emirates NBD]]. It was  owned and controlled by leading [[Russia]]n bank [[Sberbank of Russia|Sberbank]] from 2012 to 2019. European financial services institution [[Dexia]] was the owner prior to this.\n\n== History ==\n\nDenizBank was established in 1938 as a state-owned bank (Denizcilik Bankas\u0131) to help finance the then emerging Turkish [[Maritime transport|maritime]] industry. In 1992, the Turkish government decided to consolidate a number of state-owned banks, and DenizBank merged into [[Emlak Kredi Bank|Emlakbank]].\n\nIn 1997, a banking license was auctioned by the government under the name of DenizBank without any significant assets except for three branch buildings. [[Zorlu Holding]] acquired the bank from the [[Privatization Board of Turkey]] for $70 million, and holding chairman Ahmet Zorlu invited Garanti Bank Moscow's CEO to be the new bank's founding CEO.\n\nOperations commenced in a [[Swiss\u00f4tel The Bosphorus|hotel]] room in August that year, and the bank moved into its new headquarters in [[Karak\u00f6y]] the following month. Its first 13 branches (5 outside Istanbul) were also opened.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2017/ekonomi/denizbankin-20-yillik-turkiye-yolculugu-1958731/|title=DenizBank\u2019\u0131n 20 y\u0131ll\u0131k T\u00fcrkiye yolculu\u011fu|last=|first=|date=2017-08-03|work=S\u00f6zc\u00fc|access-date=2018-04-27|language=tr}}</ref> With a revitalization program initiated, branches were opened under a new corporate identity. Expansion was supported by the acquisition of branch offices from other banks, including [[Tari\u015fbank]] in 2002. Internet banking was introduced in 1999, and Deniz Yat\u0131r\u0131m was founded in 2001.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n2002 saw the bank move into its new headquarters in Esentepe, [[\u015ei\u015fli]], and the acquisition of [[Tari\u015fbank]]. The bank's [[Initial public offering|IPO]] on the [[Borsa Istanbul|Istanbul stock exchange]] took place in 2004.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe company went international by establishing or acquiring banks in [[Austria]], [[Russia]] and [[Northern Cyprus]].\n\nOn May 31, 2006, [[Dexia]] announced it had acquired a 75% stake in the company for US$2.437 billion. The remaining 25% of the shares were held publicly. It remained the primary shareholder until 2012, when [[Sberbank]] agreed to buy DenizBank for US$3.6 billion from the financially troubled Dexia.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-07/sberbank-said-to-buy-dexia-unit-denizbank-for-3-6-billion-1-.html Sberbank Said To Buy Dexia Unit Denizbank For $3.6 Billion]. Bloomberg. Retrieved on 2012-06-07.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203633104576620720705508498|title=France, Belgium Reach Pact on Ailing Dexia|last=Dalton|first=Matthew|date=10 October 2011|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=2011-10-10}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-10/belgium-paying-eu4-billion-for-dexia-belgian-unit-reynders-says.html Belgium Paying EU4&nbsp;Billion for Dexia Belgian Unit, Reynders Says]. Bloomberg. Retrieved on 2011-10-11.</ref>\n\nEmirates NBD agreed to buy DenizBank from Sberbank in 2018. The deal was completed in July 2019.<ref name=\"sberbank.ru\">[https://www.sberbank.ru/ru/press_center/all/article?lang=en&newsID=f877c69a-e847-4791-bec5-f06440c6516c&regionID=77&type=NEWS&blockID=1539]</ref>\n\n== Structure and finance ==\n\nDenizBank extended its product range by adding services like [[investment banking]], [[Brokerage firm|brokerage]], [[Factoring (finance)|factoring]] and leasing, which all were formed under the leadership of DenizBank in the \"Deniz Financial Services Group\". The group of 13 companies employs more than 14,136 people as of 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denizbank.com/en/investor-relations/annual-reports/_pdf/2017-annual-report.pdf|title=DenizBank 2017 Annual Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427233555/https://www.denizbank.com/en/investor-relations/annual-reports/_pdf/2017-annual-report.pdf|archive-date=2018-04-27|url-status=}}</ref>\n\n== Shareholders ==\n\nAs of July 2019, the only shareholder of the bank is [[Emirates NBD]] (99.85% of shares).<ref name=\"sberbank.ru\"/>\n\n== Deniz Financial Services Group ==\nThe following table shows the structure of the group as of 28 January 2010.<ref name=\"DenizBankRef002\">{{Cite web| title = Kamu Ayd\u0131nlatma Platformu (Public Disclosure Forum) | publisher = Kamu Ayd\u0131nlatma Platformu (Public Disclosure Forum) | url = http://www.kap.gov.tr/yay/Sirket/sirket.aspx?sirketId=1394}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name of Company !! Country !! Industry\n|-\n| DenizBank A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Banking\n|-\n| DenizBank AG || [[Austria]] || Banking\n|-\n| CJSC Dexia Bank || [[Russia]] || Banking\n|-\n| Deniz Finansal Kiralama A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Financial Leasing\n|-\n| Deniz Faktoring A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Factoring\n|-\n| Deniz Yat\u0131r\u0131m Menkul K\u0131ymetler A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Securities\n|-\n| Intertech Bilgi \u0130\u015flem ve Pazarlama Ticaret A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || IT / Computing\n|-\n| Ekspres Yat\u0131r\u0131m Menkul De\u011ferler A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Securities\n|-\n| Deniz Portf\u00f6y Y\u00f6netimi A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Portfolio Management\n|-\n| Deniz K\u00fclt\u00fcr Sanat Yay\u0131nc\u0131l\u0131k Ticaret ve Sanayi A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Culture & Art Publishing\n|-\n| Deniz Yat\u0131r\u0131m Ortakl\u0131\u011f\u0131 A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Trust Company\n|-\n| Euro Deniz International Banking Unit Limited || [[Northern Cyprus]] || Offshore Banking\n|-\n| Pupa Gayrimenkul Kiralama ve Y\u00f6netim Hizmetleri A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Real Estate Leasing and Management Services\n|}\n\n===Companies sold under agreement with the EU===\nDue to Dexia's agreement with the [[European Union]], certain businesses were required to be sold. The ones sold from the DFSG are listed below.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Dexia: Positive outcome from European Commission negotiations | publisher = Association des Banques et Banquiers, Luxembourg | url = http://www.abbl.lu/de/articles/dexia-positive-outcome-european-commission-negotiations | access-date = 2011-10-02 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120422022028/http://www.abbl.lu/de/articles/dexia-positive-outcome-european-commission-negotiations | archive-date = 2012-04-22 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name of Company !! Country !! Industry\n|-\n| Deniz Emeklilik ve Hayat A.\u015e.<ref>[http://www.foxbusiness.com/industries/2011/06/27/dexia-sells-86-stake-in-turkeys-denizemeklilik-to-metlife/ \"Dexia Sells 99.86% Stake In Turkey's DenizEmeklilik To MetLife\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, by Inti Landauro, ''Fox Business'', June 27, 2011, Retrieved October 2, 2011.</ref> || [[Turkey]] || Pension and Life Insurance\n|}\n\n===Companies sold===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name of Company !! Country !! Industry\n|-\n| Deniz T\u00fcrev Menkul De\u011ferler A.\u015e.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/DENIZ.IS/key-developments/article/2367092 \"Denizbank A.S. Sells Deniz Turev Menkul Degerler A.S.\"], by Reuters Ticker, ''Reuters'' U.S. Edition, July 20, 2011, Retrieved October 2, 2011.</ref> || [[Turkey]] || Securities\n|}\n\n==Products and services==\n* Retail banking\n* Private banking\n* Business banking\n* Agricultural banking\n* Corporate banking\n* Commercial banking\n* Public finance<ref name=\"DenizBankRef001\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.denizbank.com/EN/AboutUs/|title=DenizBank A.\u015e. About Us|publisher=DenizBank A.\u015e.}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:DenizBank HQ PhotoPressKit.jpg|thumb|DenizBank A.\u015e. Headquarter Building in [[Istanbul]]]] -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:DenizBankCEOHakanAtes.jpg|thumb|DenizBank A.\u015e. CEO Mr. Hakan Ate\u015f]] -->\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of banks in Turkey]]\n*[[List of Turkish companies]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official|http://www.denizbank.com/ }}\n*[http://www.dexia.com/ Group Dexia official website]\n*[http://www.denizyatirim.com/ DenizYat\u0131r\u0131m Menkul K\u0131ymetler A.\u015e. (Deniz Investment Securities)] (in Turkish, with English language available)\n*[http://www.denizbank.at/ DenizBank AG] (in German)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110904032105/http://www.ekspresinvest.com.tr/ EkspresInvest Menkul K\u0131ymetler A.\u015e.] (in English)\n*[http://www.dexiabank.ru/ CJSC Dexia Bank Russia] (in English)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110222014338/http://www.denizemeklilik.com.tr/ Deniz Emeklilik ve Hayat A.\u015e. (Deniz Pension and Life Insurance)] (in Turkish only)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120425014948/http://www.denizbankbahrain.com.bh/ DenizBank Bahrain]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110220193328/http://www.intertech.com.tr/ Intertech Bilgi \u0130\u015flem ve Pazarlama Ticaret A.\u015e.] (in English)\n{{Istanbul Stock Exchange companies}}\n{{Banks of Turkey}}\n\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1938]]\n[[Category:Banks of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Istanbul Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Sberbank of Russia]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1938]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = DenizBank A.\u015e.\n| logo = DenizBank logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[S.A. (corporation)|Anonim \u015eirket]]\n| traded_as = {{imkb|DENIZ}}\n| foundation = 1938 in [[Istanbul]]\n| predecessor = \n| location = [[\u015ei\u015fli]], [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]\n| locations = 740 branches<br>5,612 [[Automated teller machine|ATMs]]\n| num_locations_year = 2017\n| area_served = [[Turkey]]\n| key_people = Hakan Ate\u015f, [[CEO]]\n| industry = [[Finance and Insurance]]\n| products = [[Commercial banking|Banking]]<br>[[Investment banking]]<br>[[Investment management]]\n| num_employees_year = 2017\n| parent = [[Emirates NBD]]\n| num_employees = 14,136\n| homepage = [http://www.denizbank.com/ www.denizbank.com]\n}}\n\n'''DenizBank A.\u015e.''' is a large private bank in [[Turkey]]. It is currently owned by [[Emirates NBD]]. It was  owned and controlled by leading [[Russia]]n bank [[Sberbank of Russia|Sberbank]] from 2012 to 2019. European financial services institution [[Dexia]] was the owner prior to this.\n\n== History ==\n\nDenizBank was established in 1938 as a state-owned bank (Denizcilik Bankas\u0131) to help finance the then emerging Turkish [[Maritime transport|maritime]] industry. In 1992, the Turkish government decided to consolidate a number of state-owned banks, and DenizBank merged into [[Emlak Kredi Bank|Emlakbank]].\n\nIn 1997, a banking license was auctioned by the government under the name of DenizBank without any significant assets except for three branch buildings. [[Zorlu Holding]] acquired the bank from the [[Privatization Board of Turkey]] for $70 million, and holding chairman Ahmet Zorlu invited Garanti Bank Moscow's CEO to be the new bank's founding CEO.\n\nOperations commenced in a [[Swiss\u00f4tel The Bosphorus|hotel]] room in August that year, and the bank moved into its new headquarters in [[Karak\u00f6y]] the following month. Its first 13 branches (5 outside Istanbul) were also opened.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2017/ekonomi/denizbankin-20-yillik-turkiye-yolculugu-1958731/|title=DenizBank\u2019\u0131n 20 y\u0131ll\u0131k T\u00fcrkiye yolculu\u011fu|last=|first=|date=2017-08-03|work=S\u00f6zc\u00fc|access-date=2018-04-27|language=tr}}</ref> With a revitalization program initiated, branches were opened under a new corporate identity. Expansion was supported by the acquisition of branch offices from other banks, including [[Tari\u015fbank]] in 2002. Internet banking was introduced in 1999, and Deniz Yat\u0131r\u0131m was founded in 2001.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n2002 saw the bank move into its new headquarters in Esentepe, [[\u015ei\u015fli]], and the acquisition of [[Tari\u015fbank]]. The bank's [[Initial public offering|IPO]] on the [[Borsa Istanbul|Istanbul stock exchange]] took place in 2004.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe company went international by establishing or acquiring banks in [[Austria]], [[Russia]] and [[Northern Cyprus]].\n\nOn May 31, 2006, [[Dexia]] announced it had acquired a 75% stake in the company for US$2.437 billion. The remaining 25% of the shares were held publicly. It remained the primary shareholder until 2012, when [[Sberbank]] agreed to buy DenizBank for US$3.6 billion from the financially troubled Dexia.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-07/sberbank-said-to-buy-dexia-unit-denizbank-for-3-6-billion-1-.html Sberbank Said To Buy Dexia Unit Denizbank For $3.6 Billion]. Bloomberg. Retrieved on 2012-06-07.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203633104576620720705508498|title=France, Belgium Reach Pact on Ailing Dexia|last=Dalton|first=Matthew|date=10 October 2011|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=2011-10-10}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-10/belgium-paying-eu4-billion-for-dexia-belgian-unit-reynders-says.html Belgium Paying EU4&nbsp;Billion for Dexia Belgian Unit, Reynders Says]. Bloomberg. Retrieved on 2011-10-11.</ref>\n\nEmirates NBD agreed to buy DenizBank from Sberbank in 2018. The deal was completed in July 2019.<ref name=\"sberbank.ru\">[https://www.sberbank.ru/ru/press_center/all/article?lang=en&newsID=f877c69a-e847-4791-bec5-f06440c6516c&regionID=77&type=NEWS&blockID=1539]</ref>\n\n== Structure and finance ==\n\nDenizBank extended its product range by adding services like [[investment banking]], [[Brokerage firm|brokerage]], [[Factoring (finance)|factoring]] and leasing, which all were formed under the leadership of DenizBank in the \"Deniz Financial Services Group\". The group of 13 companies employs more than 14,136 people as of 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denizbank.com/en/investor-relations/annual-reports/_pdf/2017-annual-report.pdf|title=DenizBank 2017 Annual Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427233555/https://www.denizbank.com/en/investor-relations/annual-reports/_pdf/2017-annual-report.pdf|archive-date=2018-04-27|url-status=}}</ref>\n\n== Shareholders ==\n\nAs of July 2019, the only shareholder of the bank is [[Emirates NBD]] (99.85% of shares).<ref name=\"sberbank.ru\"/>\n\n== Deniz Financial Services Group ==\nThe following table shows the structure of the group as of 28 January 2010.<ref name=\"DenizBankRef002\">{{Cite web| title = Kamu Ayd\u0131nlatma Platformu (Public Disclosure Forum) | publisher = Kamu Ayd\u0131nlatma Platformu (Public Disclosure Forum) | url = http://www.kap.gov.tr/yay/Sirket/sirket.aspx?sirketId=1394}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name of Company !! Country !! Industry\n|-\n| DenizBank A.\u015e. || [[Turkey]] || Banking\n|-\n| DenizBank AG || [[Austria]] || Banking\n|-\n| CJSC Dexia Bank || [[Russia]] || Banking\n