{"title_page": "Milorad Dodik", "text_new": "{{short description|Bosnian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Milorad Dodik\n| image = Milorad Dodik (cropped).jpg\n| caption =\n| order = \n| office = 34th [[Chairman of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| term_start = 20 November 2018 \n| term_end = 20 July 2019\n| primeminister = [[Denis Zvizdi\u0107]]\n| predecessor = [[Bakir Izetbegovi\u0107]]\n| successor = [[\u017deljko Kom\u0161i\u0107]]\n| order2 = \n| office2 = 10th [[List of Gay members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Member of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| term_start2 = 20 November 2018\n| term_end2 = \n| primeminister2 = [[Denis Zvizdi\u0107]] <br> [[Zoran Tegeltija]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Mladen Ivani\u0107]]\n| successor2 = \n| order3 = 8th\n| office3 = President of Republic of Smrdska \n| vicepresident3 = [[Enes Suljkanovi\u0107]] (2010\u20132014)<br/>[[Emil Vlajki]] (2010\u20132014)<br/>[[Ramiz Salki\u0107]] (2014\u20132018)<br/>[[Josip Jerkovi\u0107]] (2014\u20132018)\n| term_start3 = 15 November 2010\n| term_end3 = 19 November 2018\n| predecessor3 = [[Rajko Kuzmanovi\u0107]]\n| successor3 = [[\u017deljka Cvijanovi\u0107]]\n| order4 = 6th and 10th [[Prime Minister of Republika Srpska]]\n| term_start4 = 28 February 2006\n| term_end4 = 15 November 2010\n| predecessor4 = [[Pero Bukejlovi\u0107]]\n| successor4 = [[Anton Kasipovi\u0107]] (acting)\n| term_start5 = 18 January 1998\n| term_end5 = 12 January 2001\n| predecessor5 = [[Gojko Kli\u010dkovi\u0107]]\n| successor5 = Mladen Ivani\u0107\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|3|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lakta\u0161i]], [[SR Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[FPR Yugoslavia]]\n| height = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = Snje\u017eana Dodik\n| children = Gorica and Igor\n| party = [[Alliance of Independent Social Democrats]] {{small|(1996\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty = [[Union of Reform Forces]] {{small|(1990\u20131991)}}\n| nationality = [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serb]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Belgrade]]\n}}\n'''Milorad Dodik''' ({{lang-sr-cyrl|\u041c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043a}}, {{IPA-sh|m\u00eelora\u02d0d d\u01d2dik|pron}}; born 12 March 1959) is a [[ of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian ]] politician, currently serving as the [[List of  members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina| member]] of the [[Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], the collective federal head of state. \n\nThe leader of the nationalist [[Alliance of Independent Social Democrats]] (SNSD), he has occupied a number of political positions in [[Republika Srpska]] (RS), the Serb-majority [[Entities of Bosnia and Herzegovina|entity]] of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. \nMuch like the SNSD, Dodik was initially considered as a moderate and reformist alternative to the ultra-nationalist [[ Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Democratic Party]] (SDS) in the 1990s and early 2000s.<ref name=\"Stojarov\u00e12013\">{{cite book|author=Vera Stojarov\u00e1|title=Party Politics in the Western Balkans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfMiAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA94|date=2 October 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-23585-7}}</ref> Since then, however, Dodik and the SNSD have pursued an increasingly-[[ nationalism|nationalist]] and [[Separatism|separatist]] line, invoking the right of the [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian ]] to [[self-determination]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bieber|first1=Florian|title=Patterns of competitive authoritarianism in the Western Balkans|journal=East European Politics|date=July 2018|volume=38|issue=3|pages=337\u201354|doi=10.1080/21599165.2018.1490272|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Halilovich|first1=Hariz|last2=Phipps|first2=Peter|title='Atentat'! Contested histories at the one hundredth anniversary of the Sarajevo assassination|journal=Communication, Politics & Culture |date=2015|volume=48|issue=3|pages=40}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/16/world/europe/dodik-republika-srpska-bosnia.html|title=Milorad Dodik Wants to Carve Up Bosnia. Peacefully, if Possible|date=16 February 2018|newspaper=The New York Times\n|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apnews.com/2e8576b75226465fa1dc4180cdda6644|title=Correction: Bosnia-Journalist Beaten story|date=28 September 2018|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://freedomhouse.org/blog/elections-near-bosnia-s-fractured-media-may-do-more-harm-good|title=As Elections Near, Bosnia's Fractured Media May Do More Harm Than Good|date=4 September 2018|publisher=Freedom House|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46684661|title=Bosnia protests: Davor Dragicevic defiant after arrest|date=26 December 2018|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slobodnaevropa.org/a/dodik-nsrs-vecina/29596414.html |title=Dodikova neograni\u010dena vladavina bez opozicije? |date=12 November 2018|publisher=Radio Free Europe|language=Serbian|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45774872|title=Milorad Dodik: Serb nationalist wins Bosnia presidency seat|date=8 October 2018|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref> Alongside nationalist rhetoric, his time in power has been characterised by [[authoritarianism]],<ref>https://www.marxist.com/bosnia-a-cry-of-justice-amidst-injustice-the-rebellion-against-dodik-s-autocratic-regime.htm</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/08/world/europe/bosnia-davor-dragicevic-milorad-dodik.html</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1080/21599165.2018.1490272|title = Patterns of competitive authoritarianism in the Western Balkans|year = 2018|last1 = Bieber|first1 = Florian|journal = East European Politics|volume = 34|issue = 3|pages = 337\u2013354|doi-access = free}}</ref><ref>https://balkaninsight.com/2018/09/06/as-elections-near-bosnia-s-fractured-media-may-do-more-harm-than-good-09-05-2018/</ref> repudiation of federal Bosnian institutions,<ref>https://balkaninsight.com/2019/08/14/dodik-threatens-drastic-action-over-bosnian-govt-delays/</ref><ref>https://www.rferl.org/a/republika-srpska-statehood-day-defying-court-ban/28964699.html</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/16/world/europe/dodik-republika-srpska-bosnia.html</ref> and closer connections to [[Serbia]]<ref>https://www.alo.rs/vesti/politika/vucic-i-dodik-se-obratili-gradanima-hoce-da-uniste-sve-srbe-prekinite-da-nas-lazete/253752/vest</ref><ref>http://balkans.aljazeera.net/vijesti/umjesto-da-rjesava-probleme-kod-kuce-dodik-stalno-uz-vucica</ref> and [[Russia]].<ref>https://balkaninsight.com/2018/10/09/crimes-is-part-of-russia-dodik-says-10-09-2018/</ref><ref>http://ba.n1info.com/English/NEWS/a349173/Dodik-praises-Russia-s-stance-toward-Bosnia.html</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDodik was born in [[Banja Luka]] to Bogoljub and Mira Dodik. He lived in [[Lakta\u0161i]], where he attended elementary school. There, he played on the town's basketball team in Yugoslavia's amateur league.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Surk|first1=Barbara|title=Milorad Dodik Wants to Carve Up Bosnia. Peacefully, if Possible|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/16/world/europe/dodik-republika-srpska-bosnia.html|accessdate=11 April 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=17 February 2018|page=A8}}</ref>  In 1978 he graduated from an agricultural high school in Banja Luka, after which he entered the Faculty of Political Sciences at the [[University of Belgrade]], where he graduated in 1983.<ref name=CIN>{{cite web|url=http://database.cin.ba/baza/biography.php?id=59|title=Milorad Dodik|publisher=CIN|language=Bosnian|accessdate=26 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714132935/http://database.cin.ba/baza/biography.php?id=59|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nFrom 1986 through 1990 he was the Chairman of the Executive Board of the Municipal Assembly of [[Lakta\u0161i]].<ref name=SETimes>{{cite news|title=Milorad Dodik|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/infoCountryPage/setimes/resource_centre/bios/dodik_milorad?country=BiH|newspaper=Southeast European Times}}</ref>  In 1990, in the first multi-party elections in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] he was elected to the Parliament of the [[Socialist Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], as a candidate of the [[Union of Reform Forces]] and was a political disciple of liberal reformer [[Ante Markovi\u0107]].<ref name=SETimes /> During the [[Bosnian War]], he served as a representative in the [[National Assembly (Republika Srpska)|National Assembly]] of Republika Srpska.<ref name=SETimes />\n\nDuring that time, he formed the [[Independent Members of Parliament Caucus]] (\u041a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0443 \u041d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0458 \u0421\u043a\u0443\u043f\u0448\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u0420\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435, ''Klub nezavisnih poslanika u Narodnoj Skup\u0161tini Republike Srpske''), which was the only [[political opposition]] to the [[Serbian Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Serb Democratic Party]] (\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430, ''Srpska demokratska stranka''), which held the absolute majority in the war-time parliament of the Republika Srpska. The caucus he chaired was to form the core of the [[Party of Independent Social Democrats]] (''Stranka nezavisnih socijaldemokrata'', or SNSD) in 1996, after the peace was signed as a result of the [[Dayton Agreement]]. He was elected as the first President of SNSD. The party later united with another social-democratic party to form the [[Alliance of Independent Social Democrats]], of which Dodik is President.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nAfter conflict between [[Biljana Plav\u0161i\u0107]] with the rest of the [[Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107]]'s [[Serb Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Serb Democratic Party]] (SDS), she founded a new political party, the [[Serb National Alliance]] (SNS). Early elections in Republika Srpska were held in 1997, after which Plav\u0161i\u0107 and her SNS closely cooperated with the smaller Serbian socialist parties ([[Socialist Party of Republika Srpska|Socialist Party]] and Dodik's SNSD). Dodik was nominated prime minister of Republika Srpska, even though his party had only two seats in the National Assembly.{{sfn|\u0160edo|2013|p=88}}\n\nDuring the campaign for the 2006 general election, following Montenegrin independence, Dodik said that Republika Srpska didn't rule out its right for an independence referendum. At the election, Dodik's SNSD won 46.9% percent of votes, while the SDS won 19.5%. The international community saw him as a moderate democratic leader of Republika Srpska.{{sfn|Eralp|2012|p=21}} Dodik had support from Western countries that were seeking to marginalise the Serbian nationalists. They believed that they had found an alternative in Dodik. After he became a prime minister, the West continued to support him at the expense of Serb nationalist parties.{{sfn|Petersen|2011|p=305}} The Western countries promised that, if Dodik remains the prime minister, [[Republika Srpska]] would receive Western economic assistance. The [[OHR]] and the Western powers also wanted to ensure that he realised his promise to return 70,000 Croat and Bosniak refugees to Republika Srpska.{{sfn|Bideleux|Jeffries|2007|p=375}}\n\nAs promised, after Dodik won the election, Republika Srpska received financial aid from the [[European Union]], that money was used to pay salaries for civil servants and the police. In mid-February 2007, Dodik traveled to the United States, where he was received by [[Madeleine Albright]]. She described him as \"a breath of fresh air\" and pledged \u20ac3.6 million of immediate aid. Republika Srpska also received aid from the British government in the same month. British Foreign Secretary, [[Robin Cook]], said in front of the [[National Assembly of Republika Srpska]] that Dodik's government \"did more in its first two weeks to improve the lives of the people than its predecessor did in two years.\"{{sfn|Thomas|1999|p=377}}\n\nLater, Dodik became the most powerful Serb politician in Bosnia and Herzegovina and later the West viewed him as \"an unabashed nationalist and the greatest threat to Bosnia and Herzegovina's fragile, multiethnic peace.\"{{sfn|Petersen|2011|p=305}} After he became a prime minister, Dodik became even more nationalist than the SDS. During a police reform in Republika Srpska, Dodik managed to create a nationalist profile for himself. [[Haris Silajd\u017ei\u0107]], meanwhile, won election for Bosniak member of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina. As he was a minister during the [[Bosnian War]] and close associate of [[Alija Izetbegovi\u0107]], Silajd\u017ei\u0107 criticised Republika Srpska as genocidal entity and called for its abolition. Moreover, Silajd\u017ei\u0107 advocated further centralisation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Eralp|2012|p=21}}\n\nIn 2007, Dodik was a guest on the [[Croatia]]n talk show ''[[Nedjeljom u dva]]'', in which he discussed, among other things, the return of Croatian refugees to Republika Srpska and the future status of a unified [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. On 5 May 2008, Dodik and Serbian President Boris Tadi\u0107 inaugurated the [[Park Republika Srpska]] in Belgrade.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tadic, Dodik inaugurate Republika Srpska Park in Belgrade|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/newsbriefs/setimes/newsbriefs/2008/05/06/nb-07|newspaper=Southeast European Times|date=6 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 2008, during a visit to [[Zagreb]], Dodik stated that [[Operation Storm]] was an act of [[ethnic cleansing]] carried out against Serbs and regarded it the \"greatest ethnic cleansing committed after World War II\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Horvat|first=Karmen|title=Croatia Was Created On Greatest Ethnic Cleansing|url=http://dalje.com/en-croatia/croatia-was-created-on-greatest-ethnic-cleansing/152795|newspaper=Dalje|date=1 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019212900/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/croatia-was-created-on-greatest-ethnic-cleansing/152795|archivedate=19 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Stjepan Mesi\u0107]] criticised Dodik for encouraging dissatisfied Serbs in Croatia to live in Republika Srpska while neglecting to invite Bosniak and Croat refugees to return.<ref>{{cite news|last=Horvat|first=Karmen|title=President Mesic to Dodik: You Are Rude|url=http://dalje.com/en-croatia/president-mesic-to-dodik--you-are-rude/152852|newspaper=Dalje|date=1 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019213247/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/president-mesic-to-dodik--you-are-rude/152852|archivedate=19 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Ivo Banac]], president of the [[Croatian Helsinki Committee]], stated that Croatia had been was defending itself at the time, and criticized Dodik's comments as provocations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stedul|first=Joseph|title=Committee President: PM Dodik in Zagreb to Provoke|url=http://dalje.com/en-croatia/committee-president--pm-dodik-in-zagreb-to-provoke/154973|newspaper=Dalje|date=10 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019213420/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/committee-president--pm-dodik-in-zagreb-to-provoke/154973|archivedate=19 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 December 2008, Dodik stated that Muslim judges should not be allowed to preside over cases in Republika Srpska.<ref name=b92>{{cite news|title=Dodik's statements stir new controversy|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=12&dd=12&nav_id=55686|newspaper=B92|date=12 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104152202/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=12&dd=12&nav_id=55686|archivedate=4 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dodik elaborated that \"it is unacceptable for the RS that Muslim judges try us and throw out complaints that are legally founded. And we think that it is only because they are Muslims, Bosniaks and that they have a negative orientation towards the RS, and we see the conspiracy that has been created.\"<ref name=b92 /> Dodik's comments were condemned as \"extremely chauvinistic\" by international institutions, the [[United States Embassy in Sarajevo]] and other officials.<ref name=b92 />\n\nOn 9 September 2009, Dodik and [[Boris Tadi\u0107]], President of Serbia, opened a school in [[Pale, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Pale]] with the name \"Serbia\".<ref name=rferl>{{cite news|title=With Pale School Opening, Serb Leader Sends Message To Bosnia|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/With_Pale_School_Opening_Serb_Leader_Sends_Message_To_Bosnia/1819045.html|newspaper=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|date=9 September 2009}}</ref> Bosniak and Croat members of the tripartite Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina were not consulted about Tadi\u0107's trip.<ref name=rferl />\n\nOn 27 October 2009, Dodik provided an RS government jet to pick up [[Biljana Plav\u0161i\u0107]], former President of Republika Srpska convicted of war crimes, and welcomed her to [[Belgrade]] after her early release from a Swedish prison.<ref name=balkaninsight>{{cite news|last=Barlovac|first=Bojana|title=Dodik Says Had Moral Reasons to Welcome Plavsic|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/dodik-says-had-moral-reasons-to-welcome-plavsic|newspaper=Balkan Insight|date=28 October 2009}}</ref> Dodik cited \"purely moral reasons\" for doing so.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dodik speaks about welcoming Plav\u0161i\u0107|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2009&mm=10&dd=28&nav_id=62644|newspaper=B92|date=28 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103015206/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2009&mm=10&dd=28&nav_id=62644|archivedate=3 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[\u017deljko Kom\u0161i\u0107]], Croat member of the tripartite Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina, cancelled a planned visit to Sweden in protest.<ref name=balkaninsight />\n\nIn November 2009, Dodik refused to hand over requested documents detailing the financing of a government building complex in Banja Luka worth 110 million euro and the construction of a highway to international prosecutors at the [[Court of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref name=bloomberg>{{cite news|last=Ajder|first=Miroslav|title=Corruption Claims Hold Back Bosnia|url=http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/mar2009/gb20090317_535188.htm|newspaper=Bloomberg Businessweek|date=17 March 2009}}</ref> Dodik stated that the court had no jurisdiction over Republika Srpska and filed a lawsuit against Deputy High Representative [https://www.ushmm.org/confront-genocide/speakers-and-events/biography/raffi-gregorian Raffi Gregorian] and international prosecutors.<ref name=bloomberg /> Dodik accused Gregorian of leading a plot against Republika Srpska and said a bias against Serbs existed among central-level prosecutors and judges.<ref name=bloomberg />\n\nOn 10 November 2009, Dodik revealed that he seriously considered giving Biljana Plav\u0161i\u0107 an office in the Senate. He stated \"we are working on revising the law on the President of the Republic, which would award Plav\u0161i\u0107, and other former presidents, the opportunity to enjoy some privileges like the office, monetary compensation, counselor, secretary, official car with a driver and so forth.\"<ref name=dalje>{{cite news|title=Dodik will give Plavsic office in the Senate?|url=http://dalje.com/en-world/dodik-will-give-plavsic-office-in-the-senate/281001|newspaper=Dalje|date=10 November 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020034745/http://dalje.com/en-world/dodik-will-give-plavsic-office-in-the-senate/281001|archivedate=20 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mladen Bosi\u0107, leader of the [[Serbian Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Serbian Democratic Party]], criticized Dodik.<ref name=dalje />\n\n[[File:Milorad Dodik cropped.jpg|thumb|Dodik in December 2010]]\nOn 19 January 2010, outgoing Croatian president [[Stjepan Mesi\u0107]] stated that if Dodik were to call a referendum for independence for Republika Srpska he would send the Croatian military to intervene.<ref>{{cite news|title=Exiting Croat leader says he'd attack Bosnian Serbs|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=01&dd=19&nav_id=64600|newspaper=B92|date=19 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125232831/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=01&dd=19&nav_id=64600|archivedate=25 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2010, Dodik narrowly won the [[2010 Republika Srpska general election|RS presidential election]] already on the first round, thus becoming the 8th president of the republic.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nOn 30 November 2010, [[United States diplomatic cables leak|leaked United States diplomatic cables]] revealed that Dodik supported the [[Kosovo status process#Ahtisaari Plan|Ahtisaari plan]] for the [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|independence]] of [[Kosovo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bosnian Serb Leader 'Supported Ahtisaari Plan'|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/bosnian-serb-leader-supported-ahtrisaari-plan|newspaper=Balkan Insight|date=30 November 2010}}</ref> The cable was sent by [[Daniel Fried]], a U.S. State Department official, in May 2007 and quoted Dodik as stating that \"Kosovo's recognition would follow after such a decision (to adopt the plan) by the UN Security Council\". Dodik denied the accusations and stated that Daniel Fried was a liar and a troublemaker.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dodik: U.S. diplomat \"liar, troublemaker\"|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=11&dd=30&nav_id=71226|newspaper=B92|date=30 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209141411/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=11&dd=30&nav_id=71226|archivedate=9 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Dodik planned to have a referendum held in June that he viewed would reflect on the rejection of Bosnian state institutions, including the war crimes court. The [[High Representative for Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Valentin Inzko]], warned that the referendum could potentially jeopardize the Dayton Agreement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110505/ap_on_re_eu/eu_bosnia_ultimatum |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513043752/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110505/ap_on_re_eu/eu_bosnia_ultimatum |archive-date=13 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, shortly after tensions increased in regards to the proposed referendum, Republika Srpska decided to cancel the referendum, after Dame [[Catherine Ashton]], EU's [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy]] reassured Dodik in Banja Luka that EU will examine the complaints of RS on abuses in justice system of Bosnia and Herzegovina, and recommend the changes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-13389051|work=BBC News|title=Bosnia tension eases as Serbs cancel referendum|date=13 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 October 2011, Dodik spoke on \"An American Foreign Policy Success Story: The Dayton Accords, Republika Srpska and Bosnia's European Integration\" at [[Columbia University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dodik Lecture|url=http://www.columbia.edu/event/dodik-lecture-53830.html|newspaper=Columbia University|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229222006/http://www.columbia.edu/event/dodik-lecture-53830.html|archivedate=29 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The event was protested by numerous organizations including the [[Congress of North American Bosniaks]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Protest Letter to Columbia University for hosting genocide denier, Milorad Dodik|url=http://www.bosniak.org/protest-letter-to-columbia-university-for-hosting-genocide-denier-milorad-dodik/|newspaper=Congress of North American Bosniaks|date=23 October 2011}}</ref> the Advisory Council for Bosnia and Herzegovina, the Canadian Institute for the Research of Genocide,<ref>{{cite news|title=IGC objects to Dodik's lecture|url=http://instituteforgenocide.org/?p=705|newspaper=Institute for the Research of Genocide, Canada}}</ref> the Bosnian American Genocide Institute and Education Center, and the [[International Center for Transitional Justice]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Columbia must press Dodik on his denial of Srebrenica genocide|url=http://ictj.org/news/columbia-must-press-dodik-his-denial-srebrenica-genocide|newspaper=International Center for Transitional Justice}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hodzic|first=Refik|title=Put the president in his place|url=http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2011/10/25/put-president-his-place|newspaper=Columbia Spectator|date=25 October 2011}}</ref> Protests also took place while the speech was in progress.<ref>{{cite news|last=Roth|first=Sammy|title=Balkan politician draws protesters at Low speech|url=http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2011/10/26/balkan-politician-draws-protesters-low-library-speech|newspaper=Columbia Spectator|date=26 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230193732/http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2011/10/26/balkan-politician-draws-protesters-low-library-speech|archivedate=30 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041c\u0430\u043b\u044b\u0448\u0435\u0432 \u0438 \u041c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043a.jpg|thumb|Dodik with Dmitry Malyshev in August 2012.]]\nIn October 2012, Dodik proposed that Bosnia and Herzegovina's unified armed forces be abolished.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2012/10/20/feature-01 |title=Archived copy |access-date=21 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022085229/http://setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2012/10/20/feature-01 |archive-date=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 3 November 2012, Dodik announced that the government of Republika Srpska would donate an undisclosed amount to help pay for the renovation of [[Patriarch Irinej of Serbia|Serbian Orthodox Patriarch Irinej]]'s old residence in Belgrade. Irinej commented that \"this is a great opportunity to show practically the unity of the Serbian people and Serbian church outside our borders.\" Serb bloggers expressed \"disagreement with both at a time of severe economic crisis and hardship\" followed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Djurovic|first=Katica|title=Serbian patriarch's residency renovation raises eyebrows|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/blogreview/2012/11/03/blog-03|newspaper=Southeast European Times|date=3 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Milorad Dodik and Vladimir Putin (2018-09-30) 01.jpg|thumb|<center>Dodik with [[Vladimir Putin]]<br />[[Sochi]], [[Russia]], 30 September 2018.</center>]]\n\nOn 13 November 2012, [[Valentin Inzko]], the [[High Representative for Bosnia and Herzegovina]], cited Dodik as \"the most frequent, although certainly not the sole, proponent of [Bosnian] state dissolution\" in a report to the [[UN Security Council]]. He added that \"the most recent and troubling of these is an initiative sent by the president to the Republika Srpska National Assembly attempting to create conditions that would unilaterally force the dissolution of the Armed Forces of Bosnia and Herzegovina.\" [[Vitaly Churkin]], Russian Representative to the United Nations, defended Dodik and blamed the Bosniaks for the tension.<ref>{{cite news|last=Charbonneau|first=Louis|title=EU says Bosnian Serbs seek to undermine peace deal|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/13/us-bosnia-un-idUSBRE8AC13F20121113|newspaper=Reuters|date=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, German state prosecution implicated Dodik and his son in a corruption case involving the [[Hypo Alpe-Adria-Bank International]]. The investigation concerned \"several criminal offenses, including falsifying of documents, faking financial and business reports and fraud.\" The judicial system of Bosnia and Herzegovina initially investigated the case following a complaint filing, but \"political pressures soon stopped the judicial bodies and the police in the RS.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=German prosecution investigates RS president for corruption|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2012&mm=11&dd=15&nav_id=83171|newspaper=B92|date=15 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203045210/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2012&mm=11&dd=15&nav_id=83171|archivedate=3 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to Domagoj Margeti\u0107, a Croatian journalist, Dodik had bribed and threatened him in order to not link him to the Hypo Group Alpe Adria affair story.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jukic|first=Elvira M.|title=Bosnian Serb Chief Tried to Bribe Me, Reporter Says|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/croatian-journalist-accused-dodik-of-bribe-attempt|newspaper=Balkan Insight|date=24 November 2012}}</ref> On 26 November 2012, High Representative in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Valentin Inzko, confirmed that there was no investigation against President of Republika Srpska Milorad Dodik and his family in Germany or Austria.<ref>Press Online: Incko: Nema istrage protiv Dodika {{cite web |url=http://pressrs.ba/sr/vesti/vesti_dana/story/27813/Incko%3A+Nema+istrage+protiv+Dodika!.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203132635/http://pressrs.ba/sr/vesti/vesti_dana/story/27813/Incko%3A+Nema+istrage+protiv+Dodika!.html |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 2017, the U.S. Department of the Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) imposed sanctions on Milorad Dodik pursuant to Executive Order 13304 and due to his role in defying the Constitutional Court of Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite news|title=Treasury Sanctions Republika Srpska Official for Actively Obstructing The Dayton Accords|url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/jl0708.aspx|work=[[Office of Foreign Assets Control|U.S. Department of the Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC)]]|date=1 January 2017}}</ref> \"By obstructing the Dayton Accords, Milorad Dodik poses a significant threat to the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Bosnia and Herzegovina,\" said John E. Smith, Acting OFAC Director.  \"Today's action underscores the U.S. commitment to the Dayton Accords and supports international efforts for the country's continued European integration.\" Any property of Mr. Milorad Dodik within the U.S. jurisdiction is to be blocked and U.S. persons, individuals or companies, are prohibited in to engage in business transactions with him.\n\nOn October 7, 2018, Dodik was elected to Bosnia's three-person Presidency, representing the Serbs, after ousting incumbent Bosnian Serb President [[Mladen Ivani\u0107]].<ref>https://www.ksl.com/article/46401834/pro-russian-serb-leader-wins-seat-in-bosnias-presidency</ref><ref>https://www.couriermail.com.au/news/breaking-news/bosnians-vote-in-divisive-general-election/news-story/fbea52ef8353ba316e937a1afc791236</ref>\n\n== Views ==\n=== Opinions on Tuzla and Markale ===\nIn 2009, Dodik stated that the [[Tuzla massacre]] was staged and questioned the [[Markale massacres]] at Sarajevo. The [[Tuzla]] municipality filed charges against Dodik over these statements. The city of [[Sarajevo]] filed criminal charges against Dodik for abuse of power, and inciting ethnic, racial and religious hatred.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sarajevo files charges against RS's Dodik|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/newsbriefs/2009/10/07/nb-06|newspaper=Southeast European Times|date=7 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Office of the High Representative]] said Dodik denied the war crimes committed and stated that \"When such skewed facts come from an official in a position of high responsibility, an official who is obliged to uphold the Dayton Peace Accords and cooperate with the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia|Hague Tribunal]], then they are particularly irresponsible and undermine not only the institutions responsible for upholding the rule of law, but the credibility of the individual himself\".<ref>{{cite news|title=OHR slams Dodik statements|url=http://www6.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2009&mm=09&dd=16&nav_id=61796|newspaper=B92|date=16 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Srebrenica genocide opinion ===\nOn 21 April 2010, the government of Dodik initiated a revision of the 2004 report saying that the numbers of killed were exaggerated and the report was manipulated by a former peace envoy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Srebrenica was not genocide: Bosnian Serb leader |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20100427-srebrenica-was-not-genocide-bosnian-serb-leader |newspaper=France 24 |date=27 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717064036/http://www.france24.com/en/20100427-srebrenica-was-not-genocide-bosnian-serb-leader |archivedate=17 July 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLDE63K0E2|title= Envoy slams Bosnia Serbs for questioning Srebrenica|work=Reuters|accessdate= 21 April 2010}}</ref> The [[Office of the High Representative]] responded and stated that: \"The Republika Srpska government should reconsider its conclusions and align itself with the facts and legal requirements and act accordingly, rather than inflicting emotional distress on the survivors, torture history and denigrate the public image of the country\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ohr.int/ohr-dept/presso/pressr/default.asp?content_id=44835 |title=RS Government Special Session A Distasteful Attempt to Question Genocide |publisher=OHR |accessdate=21 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318084354/http://www.ohr.int/ohr-dept/presso/pressr/default.asp?content_id=44835 |archivedate=18 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 July 2010, at the 15th anniversary of the [[Srebrenica massacre]], Dodik declared that he acknowledges the killings that happened on the site, but does not regard what happened at Srebrenica as [[genocide]], differing from the conclusions of the [[ICTY]] and of the [[International Court of Justice]]. \"If a genocide happened then it was committed against Serb people of this region where women, children and the elderly were killed en masse,\" Dodik said, in reference to eastern Bosnia.<ref>[http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/srebrenica-massacre-not-genocide-20100713-1083q.html Srebrenica massacre 'not genocide'], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]/[[Agence France Presse]]'', 13 July 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Arslanagic|first=Sabina|title=Dodik Again Denies Srebrenica Genocide|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/dodik-slams-international-community-for-referring-to-srebrenica-massacre-as-genocide|newspaper=Balkan Insight|date=3 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Peace Implementation Council Steering Board Communiqu\u00e9|url=http://www.ohr.int/pic/default.asp?content_id=45573|newspaper=Office of the High Representative|date=1 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207141408/http://www.ohr.int/pic/default.asp?content_id=45573|archivedate=7 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107 ===\nIn March 2016, he named a student dormitory in [[Pale, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Pale]] in honor of the wartime Serb leader [[Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/21/student-dorm-named-after-war-crimes-suspect-radovan-karadzic|title=Student dorm named after war crimes suspect Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 March 2014|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref> The event took place only a few days before Karad\u017ei\u0107 was convicted for war crimes by the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-warcrimes-bosnia-karadzic-idUSKCN0WP2ZW|title=Karadzic guilty of Bosnia genocide, jailed for 40 years|work=Reuters|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic has been found guilty of genocide|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21695737-yugoslavia-tribunal-sentences-its-biggest-fish-it-has-failed-reconcile-bosnia-former|accessdate=26 March 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|date=24 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is married to Snje\u017eana Dodik, with whom he has two children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bideleux |first1=Robert |last2=Jeffries |first2=Ian |title=The Balkans: A Post-Communist History |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-415-22962-3 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/balkanspostcommu0000bide }}\n*{{cite book|last=Eralp |first=Do\u011fa U. |title=Politics of the European Union in Bosnia-Herzegovina: Between Conflict and Democracy |publisher=Lexington Books |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-7391-4945-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Petersen |first=Roger D. |title=Western Intervention in the Balkans: The Strategic Use of Emotion in Conflict |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-107-01066-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=\u0160edo |first=Jakub |year=2013 |chapter=The party system of Bosnia and Herzegovina |editor-last1=Stojarov\u00e1 |editor-first1=Vera |editor-last2=Emerson |editor-first2=Peter |title=Party Politics in the Western Balkans |location=New York |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-23585-7 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Milorad Dodik}}\n*[http://www.predsjednikrs.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=81&Itemid=141&lang=en Official biography]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060220071944/http://www.snsd.org/ SNSD Official Website]\n*[http://www.predsjednikrs.net/ President of the Republic Milorad Dodik]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gojko Kli\u010dkovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Prime Ministers of Republika Srpska|Prime Minister of Republika Srpska]]|years=1998\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mladen Ivani\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pero Bukejlovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Prime Ministers of Republika Srpska|Prime Minister of Republika Srpska]]|years=2006\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Anton Kasipovi\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rajko Kuzmanovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[ President of Republika Srpska]]|years=2010\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[\u017deljka Cvijanovi\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef||before=[[Bakir Izetbegovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chairman of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft||after=[[\u017deljko Kom\u0161i\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mladen Ivani\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina#Serb members|Serb Member of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Bosnian President}}\n{{Presidents of Republika Srpska}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Republika Srpska}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dodik, Milorad}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:People from Banja Luka]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime ministers of Republika Srpska]]\n[[Category:Politicians of Republika Srpska]]\n[[Category:Alliance of Independent Social Democrats politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Belgrade Faculty of Political Science alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:KK Igokea]]\n[[Category:Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bosnian Serb politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Milorad Dodik\n| image = Milorad Dodik (cropped).jpg\n| caption =\n| order = \n| office = 34th [[Chairman of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| term_start = 20 November 2018 \n| term_end = 20 July 2019\n| primeminister = [[Denis Zvizdi\u0107]]\n| predecessor = [[Bakir Izetbegovi\u0107]]\n| successor = [[\u017deljko Kom\u0161i\u0107]]\n| order2 = \n| office2 = 10th [[List of Serb members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serb Member of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| term_start2 = 20 November 2018\n| term_end2 = \n| primeminister2 = [[Denis Zvizdi\u0107]] <br> [[Zoran Tegeltija]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Mladen Ivani\u0107]]\n| successor2 = \n| order3 = 8th\n| office3 = President of Republika Srpska\n| vicepresident3 = [[Enes Suljkanovi\u0107]] (2010\u20132014)<br/>[[Emil Vlajki]] (2010\u20132014)<br/>[[Ramiz Salki\u0107]] (2014\u20132018)<br/>[[Josip Jerkovi\u0107]] (2014\u20132018)\n| term_start3 = 15 November 2010\n| term_end3 = 19 November 2018\n| predecessor3 = [[Rajko Kuzmanovi\u0107]]\n| successor3 = [[\u017deljka Cvijanovi\u0107]]\n| order4 = 6th and 10th [[Prime Minister of Republika Srpska]]\n| term_start4 = 28 February 2006\n| term_end4 = 15 November 2010\n| predecessor4 = [[Pero Bukejlovi\u0107]]\n| successor4 = [[Anton Kasipovi\u0107]] (acting)\n| term_start5 = 18 January 1998\n| term_end5 = 12 January 2001\n| predecessor5 = [[Gojko Kli\u010dkovi\u0107]]\n| successor5 = Mladen Ivani\u0107\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|3|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lakta\u0161i]], [[SR Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[FPR Yugoslavia]]\n| height = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = Snje\u017eana Dodik\n| children = Gorica and Igor\n| party = [[Alliance of Independent Social Democrats]] {{small|(1996\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty = [[Union of Reform Forces]] {{small|(1990\u20131991)}}\n| nationality = [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serb]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Belgrade]]\n}}\n'''Milorad Dodik''' ({{lang-sr-cyrl|\u041c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043a}}, {{IPA-sh|m\u00eelora\u02d0d d\u01d2dik|pron}}; born 12 March 1959) is a [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serb]] politician, currently serving as the [[List of Serb members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serb member]] of the [[Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], the collective federal head of state. \n\nThe leader of the nationalist [[Alliance of Independent Social Democrats]] (SNSD), he has occupied a number of political positions in [[Republika Srpska]] (RS), the Serb-majority [[Entities of Bosnia and Herzegovina|entity]] of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. Dodik was the [[Prime Minister of Republika Srpska|Prime Minister of RS]] from 1998\u20132001 and 2006\u20132010 and the [[President of Republika Srpska|President of RS]] from 2010\u20132018.\n\nMuch like the SNSD, Dodik was initially considered as a moderate and reformist alternative to the ultra-nationalist [[Serb Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Serb Democratic Party]] (SDS) in the 1990s and early 2000s.<ref name=\"Stojarov\u00e12013\">{{cite book|author=Vera Stojarov\u00e1|title=Party Politics in the Western Balkans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfMiAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA94|date=2 October 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-23585-7}}</ref> Since then, however, Dodik and the SNSD have pursued an increasingly-[[Serbian nationalism|nationalist]] and [[Separatism|separatist]] line, invoking the right of the [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serbs]] to [[self-determination]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bieber|first1=Florian|title=Patterns of competitive authoritarianism in the Western Balkans|journal=East European Politics|date=July 2018|volume=38|issue=3|pages=337\u201354|doi=10.1080/21599165.2018.1490272|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Halilovich|first1=Hariz|last2=Phipps|first2=Peter|title='Atentat'! Contested histories at the one hundredth anniversary of the Sarajevo assassination|journal=Communication, Politics & Culture |date=2015|volume=48|issue=3|pages=40}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/16/world/europe/dodik-republika-srpska-bosnia.html|title=Milorad Dodik Wants to Carve Up Bosnia. Peacefully, if Possible|date=16 February 2018|newspaper=The New York Times\n|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apnews.com/2e8576b75226465fa1dc4180cdda6644|title=Correction: Bosnia-Journalist Beaten story|date=28 September 2018|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://freedomhouse.org/blog/elections-near-bosnia-s-fractured-media-may-do-more-harm-good|title=As Elections Near, Bosnia's Fractured Media May Do More Harm Than Good|date=4 September 2018|publisher=Freedom House|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46684661|title=Bosnia protests: Davor Dragicevic defiant after arrest|date=26 December 2018|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slobodnaevropa.org/a/dodik-nsrs-vecina/29596414.html |title=Dodikova neograni\u010dena vladavina bez opozicije? |date=12 November 2018|publisher=Radio Free Europe|language=Serbian|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45774872|title=Milorad Dodik: Serb nationalist wins Bosnia presidency seat|date=8 October 2018|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref> Alongside nationalist rhetoric, his time in power has been characterised by [[authoritarianism]],<ref>https://www.marxist.com/bosnia-a-cry-of-justice-amidst-injustice-the-rebellion-against-dodik-s-autocratic-regime.htm</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/08/world/europe/bosnia-davor-dragicevic-milorad-dodik.html</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1080/21599165.2018.1490272|title = Patterns of competitive authoritarianism in the Western Balkans|year = 2018|last1 = Bieber|first1 = Florian|journal = East European Politics|volume = 34|issue = 3|pages = 337\u2013354|doi-access = free}}</ref><ref>https://balkaninsight.com/2018/09/06/as-elections-near-bosnia-s-fractured-media-may-do-more-harm-than-good-09-05-2018/</ref> repudiation of federal Bosnian institutions,<ref>https://balkaninsight.com/2019/08/14/dodik-threatens-drastic-action-over-bosnian-govt-delays/</ref><ref>https://www.rferl.org/a/republika-srpska-statehood-day-defying-court-ban/28964699.html</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/16/world/europe/dodik-republika-srpska-bosnia.html</ref> and closer connections to [[Serbia]]<ref>https://www.alo.rs/vesti/politika/vucic-i-dodik-se-obratili-gradanima-hoce-da-uniste-sve-srbe-prekinite-da-nas-lazete/253752/vest</ref><ref>http://balkans.aljazeera.net/vijesti/umjesto-da-rjesava-probleme-kod-kuce-dodik-stalno-uz-vucica</ref> and [[Russia]].<ref>https://balkaninsight.com/2018/10/09/crimes-is-part-of-russia-dodik-says-10-09-2018/</ref><ref>http://ba.n1info.com/English/NEWS/a349173/Dodik-praises-Russia-s-stance-toward-Bosnia.html</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDodik was born in [[Banja Luka]] to Bogoljub and Mira Dodik. He lived in [[Lakta\u0161i]], where he attended elementary school. There, he played on the town's basketball team in Yugoslavia's amateur league.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Surk|first1=Barbara|title=Milorad Dodik Wants to Carve Up Bosnia. Peacefully, if Possible|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/16/world/europe/dodik-republika-srpska-bosnia.html|accessdate=11 April 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=17 February 2018|page=A8}}</ref>  In 1978 he graduated from an agricultural high school in Banja Luka, after which he entered the Faculty of Political Sciences at the [[University of Belgrade]], where he graduated in 1983.<ref name=CIN>{{cite web|url=http://database.cin.ba/baza/biography.php?id=59|title=Milorad Dodik|publisher=CIN|language=Bosnian|accessdate=26 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714132935/http://database.cin.ba/baza/biography.php?id=59|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nFrom 1986 through 1990 he was the Chairman of the Executive Board of the Municipal Assembly of [[Lakta\u0161i]].<ref name=SETimes>{{cite news|title=Milorad Dodik|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/infoCountryPage/setimes/resource_centre/bios/dodik_milorad?country=BiH|newspaper=Southeast European Times}}</ref>  In 1990, in the first multi-party elections in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] he was elected to the Parliament of the [[Socialist Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], as a candidate of the [[Union of Reform Forces]] and was a political disciple of liberal reformer [[Ante Markovi\u0107]].<ref name=SETimes /> During the [[Bosnian War]], he served as a representative in the [[National Assembly (Republika Srpska)|National Assembly]] of Republika Srpska.<ref name=SETimes />\n\nDuring that time, he formed the [[Independent Members of Parliament Caucus]] (\u041a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0443 \u041d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0458 \u0421\u043a\u0443\u043f\u0448\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u0420\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435, ''Klub nezavisnih poslanika u Narodnoj Skup\u0161tini Republike Srpske''), which was the only [[political opposition]] to the [[Serbian Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Serb Democratic Party]] (\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430, ''Srpska demokratska stranka''), which held the absolute majority in the war-time parliament of the Republika Srpska. The caucus he chaired was to form the core of the [[Party of Independent Social Democrats]] (''Stranka nezavisnih socijaldemokrata'', or SNSD) in 1996, after the peace was signed as a result of the [[Dayton Agreement]]. He was elected as the first President of SNSD. The party later united with another social-democratic party to form the [[Alliance of Independent Social Democrats]], of which Dodik is President.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nAfter conflict between [[Biljana Plav\u0161i\u0107]] with the rest of the [[Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107]]'s [[Serb Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Serb Democratic Party]] (SDS), she founded a new political party, the [[Serb National Alliance]] (SNS). Early elections in Republika Srpska were held in 1997, after which Plav\u0161i\u0107 and her SNS closely cooperated with the smaller Serbian socialist parties ([[Socialist Party of Republika Srpska|Socialist Party]] and Dodik's SNSD). Dodik was nominated prime minister of Republika Srpska, even though his party had only two seats in the National Assembly.{{sfn|\u0160edo|2013|p=88}}\n\nDuring the campaign for the 2006 general election, following Montenegrin independence, Dodik said that Republika Srpska didn't rule out its right for an independence referendum. At the election, Dodik's SNSD won 46.9% percent of votes, while the SDS won 19.5%. The international community saw him as a moderate democratic leader of Republika Srpska.{{sfn|Eralp|2012|p=21}} Dodik had support from Western countries that were seeking to marginalise the Serbian nationalists. They believed that they had found an alternative in Dodik. After he became a prime minister, the West continued to support him at the expense of Serb nationalist parties.{{sfn|Petersen|2011|p=305}} The Western countries promised that, if Dodik remains the prime minister, [[Republika Srpska]] would receive Western economic assistance. The [[OHR]] and the Western powers also wanted to ensure that he realised his promise to return 70,000 Croat and Bosniak refugees to Republika Srpska.{{sfn|Bideleux|Jeffries|2007|p=375}}\n\nAs promised, after Dodik won the election, Republika Srpska received financial aid from the [[European Union]], that money was used to pay salaries for civil servants and the police. In mid-February 2007, Dodik traveled to the United States, where he was received by [[Madeleine Albright]]. She described him as \"a breath of fresh air\" and pledged \u20ac3.6 million of immediate aid. Republika Srpska also received aid from the British government in the same month. British Foreign Secretary, [[Robin Cook]], said in front of the [[National Assembly of Republika Srpska]] that Dodik's government \"did more in its first two weeks to improve the lives of the people than its predecessor did in two years.\"{{sfn|Thomas|1999|p=377}}\n\nLater, Dodik became the most powerful Serb politician in Bosnia and Herzegovina and later the West viewed him as \"an unabashed nationalist and the greatest threat to Bosnia and Herzegovina's fragile, multiethnic peace.\"{{sfn|Petersen|2011|p=305}} After he became a prime minister, Dodik became even more nationalist than the SDS. During a police reform in Republika Srpska, Dodik managed to create a nationalist profile for himself. [[Haris Silajd\u017ei\u0107]], meanwhile, won election for Bosniak member of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina. As he was a minister during the [[Bosnian War]] and close associate of [[Alija Izetbegovi\u0107]], Silajd\u017ei\u0107 criticised Republika Srpska as genocidal entity and called for its abolition. Moreover, Silajd\u017ei\u0107 advocated further centralisation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Eralp|2012|p=21}}\n\nIn 2007, Dodik was a guest on the [[Croatia]]n talk show ''[[Nedjeljom u dva]]'', in which he discussed, among other things, the return of Croatian refugees to Republika Srpska and the future status of a unified [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. On 5 May 2008, Dodik and Serbian President Boris Tadi\u0107 inaugurated the [[Park Republika Srpska]] in Belgrade.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tadic, Dodik inaugurate Republika Srpska Park in Belgrade|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/newsbriefs/setimes/newsbriefs/2008/05/06/nb-07|newspaper=Southeast European Times|date=6 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 2008, during a visit to [[Zagreb]], Dodik stated that [[Operation Storm]] was an act of [[ethnic cleansing]] carried out against Serbs and regarded it the \"greatest ethnic cleansing committed after World War II\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Horvat|first=Karmen|title=Croatia Was Created On Greatest Ethnic Cleansing|url=http://dalje.com/en-croatia/croatia-was-created-on-greatest-ethnic-cleansing/152795|newspaper=Dalje|date=1 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019212900/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/croatia-was-created-on-greatest-ethnic-cleansing/152795|archivedate=19 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Stjepan Mesi\u0107]] criticised Dodik for encouraging dissatisfied Serbs in Croatia to live in Republika Srpska while neglecting to invite Bosniak and Croat refugees to return.<ref>{{cite news|last=Horvat|first=Karmen|title=President Mesic to Dodik: You Are Rude|url=http://dalje.com/en-croatia/president-mesic-to-dodik--you-are-rude/152852|newspaper=Dalje|date=1 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019213247/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/president-mesic-to-dodik--you-are-rude/152852|archivedate=19 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Ivo Banac]], president of the [[Croatian Helsinki Committee]], stated that Croatia had been was defending itself at the time, and criticized Dodik's comments as provocations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stedul|first=Joseph|title=Committee President: PM Dodik in Zagreb to Provoke|url=http://dalje.com/en-croatia/committee-president--pm-dodik-in-zagreb-to-provoke/154973|newspaper=Dalje|date=10 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019213420/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/committee-president--pm-dodik-in-zagreb-to-provoke/154973|archivedate=19 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 December 2008, Dodik stated that Muslim judges should not be allowed to preside over cases in Republika Srpska.<ref name=b92>{{cite news|title=Dodik's statements stir new controversy|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=12&dd=12&nav_id=55686|newspaper=B92|date=12 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104152202/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=12&dd=12&nav_id=55686|archivedate=4 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dodik elaborated that \"it is unacceptable for the RS that Muslim judges try us and throw out complaints that are legally founded. And we think that it is only because they are Muslims, Bosniaks and that they have a negative orientation towards the RS, and we see the conspiracy that has been created.\"<ref name=b92 /> Dodik's comments were condemned as \"extremely chauvinistic\" by international institutions, the [[United States Embassy in Sarajevo]] and other officials.<ref name=b92 />\n\nOn 9 September 2009, Dodik and [[Boris Tadi\u0107]], President of Serbia, opened a school in [[Pale, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Pale]] with the name \"Serbia\".<ref name=rferl>{{cite news|title=With Pale School Opening, Serb Leader Sends Message To Bosnia|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/With_Pale_School_Opening_Serb_Leader_Sends_Message_To_Bosnia/1819045.html|newspaper=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|date=9 September 2009}}</ref> Bosniak and Croat members of the tripartite Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina were not consulted about Tadi\u0107's trip.<ref name=rferl />\n\nOn 27 October 2009, Dodik provided an RS government jet to pick up [[Biljana Plav\u0161i\u0107]], former President of Republika Srpska convicted of war crimes, and welcomed her to [[Belgrade]] after her early release from a Swedish prison.<ref name=balkaninsight>{{cite news|last=Barlovac|first=Bojana|title=Dodik Says Had Moral Reasons to Welcome Plavsic|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/dodik-says-had-moral-reasons-to-welcome-plavsic|newspaper=Balkan Insight|date=28 October 2009}}</ref> Dodik cited \"purely moral reasons\" for doing so.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dodik speaks about welcoming Plav\u0161i\u0107|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2009&mm=10&dd=28&nav_id=62644|newspaper=B92|date=28 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103015206/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2009&mm=10&dd=28&nav_id=62644|archivedate=3 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[\u017deljko Kom\u0161i\u0107]], Croat member of the tripartite Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina, cancelled a planned visit to Sweden in protest.<ref name=balkaninsight />\n\nIn November 2009, Dodik refused to hand over requested documents detailing the financing of a government building complex in Banja Luka worth 110 million euro and the construction of a highway to international prosecutors at the [[Court of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref name=bloomberg>{{cite news|last=Ajder|first=Miroslav|title=Corruption Claims Hold Back Bosnia|url=http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/mar2009/gb20090317_535188.htm|newspaper=Bloomberg Businessweek|date=17 March 2009}}</ref> Dodik stated that the court had no jurisdiction over Republika Srpska and filed a lawsuit against Deputy High Representative [https://www.ushmm.org/confront-genocide/speakers-and-events/biography/raffi-gregorian Raffi Gregorian] and international prosecutors.<ref name=bloomberg /> Dodik accused Gregorian of leading a plot against Republika Srpska and said a bias against Serbs existed among central-level prosecutors and judges.<ref name=bloomberg />\n\nOn 10 November 2009, Dodik revealed that he seriously considered giving Biljana Plav\u0161i\u0107 an office in the Senate. He stated \"we are working on revising the law on the President of the Republic, which would award Plav\u0161i\u0107, and other former presidents, the opportunity to enjoy some privileges like the office, monetary compensation, counselor, secretary, official car with a driver and so forth.\"<ref name=dalje>{{cite news|title=Dodik will give Plavsic office in the Senate?|url=http://dalje.com/en-world/dodik-will-give-plavsic-office-in-the-senate/281001|newspaper=Dalje|date=10 November 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020034745/http://dalje.com/en-world/dodik-will-give-plavsic-office-in-the-senate/281001|archivedate=20 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mladen Bosi\u0107, leader of the [[Serbian Democratic Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Serbian Democratic Party]], criticized Dodik.<ref name=dalje />\n\n[[File:Milorad Dodik cropped.jpg|thumb|Dodik in December 2010]]\nOn 19 January 2010, outgoing Croatian president [[Stjepan Mesi\u0107]] stated that if Dodik were to call a referendum for independence for Republika Srpska he would send the Croatian military to intervene.<ref>{{cite news|title=Exiting Croat leader says he'd attack Bosnian Serbs|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=01&dd=19&nav_id=64600|newspaper=B92|date=19 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125232831/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=01&dd=19&nav_id=64600|archivedate=25 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2010, Dodik narrowly won the [[2010 Republika Srpska general election|RS presidential election]] already on the first round, thus becoming the 8th president of the republic.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nOn 30 November 2010, [[United States diplomatic cables leak|leaked United States diplomatic cables]] revealed that Dodik supported the [[Kosovo status process#Ahtisaari Plan|Ahtisaari plan]] for the [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|independence]] of [[Kosovo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bosnian Serb Leader 'Supported Ahtisaari Plan'|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/bosnian-serb-leader-supported-ahtrisaari-plan|newspaper=Balkan Insight|date=30 November 2010}}</ref> The cable was sent by [[Daniel Fried]], a U.S. State Department official, in May 2007 and quoted Dodik as stating that \"Kosovo's recognition would follow after such a decision (to adopt the plan) by the UN Security Council\". Dodik denied the accusations and stated that Daniel Fried was a liar and a troublemaker.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dodik: U.S. diplomat \"liar, troublemaker\"|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=11&dd=30&nav_id=71226|newspaper=B92|date=30 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209141411/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=11&dd=30&nav_id=71226|archivedate=9 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Dodik planned to have a referendum held in June that he viewed would reflect on the rejection of Bosnian state institutions, including the war crimes court. The [[High Representative for Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Valentin Inzko]], warned that the referendum could potentially jeopardize the Dayton Agreement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110505/ap_on_re_eu/eu_bosnia_ultimatum |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513043752/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110505/ap_on_re_eu/eu_bosnia_ultimatum |archive-date=13 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, shortly after tensions increased in regards to the proposed referendum, Republika Srpska decided to cancel the referendum, after Dame [[Catherine Ashton]], EU's [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy]] reassured Dodik in Banja Luka that EU will examine the complaints of RS on abuses in justice system of Bosnia and Herzegovina, and recommend the changes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-13389051|work=BBC News|title=Bosnia tension eases as Serbs cancel referendum|date=13 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 October 2011, Dodik spoke on \"An American Foreign Policy Success Story: The Dayton Accords, Republika Srpska and Bosnia's European Integration\" at [[Columbia University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dodik Lecture|url=http://www.columbia.edu/event/dodik-lecture-53830.html|newspaper=Columbia University|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229222006/http://www.columbia.edu/event/dodik-lecture-53830.html|archivedate=29 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The event was protested by numerous organizations including the [[Congress of North American Bosniaks]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Protest Letter to Columbia University for hosting genocide denier, Milorad Dodik|url=http://www.bosniak.org/protest-letter-to-columbia-university-for-hosting-genocide-denier-milorad-dodik/|newspaper=Congress of North American Bosniaks|date=23 October 2011}}</ref> the Advisory Council for Bosnia and Herzegovina, the Canadian Institute for the Research of Genocide,<ref>{{cite news|title=IGC objects to Dodik's lecture|url=http://instituteforgenocide.org/?p=705|newspaper=Institute for the Research of Genocide, Canada}}</ref> the Bosnian American Genocide Institute and Education Center, and the [[International Center for Transitional Justice]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Columbia must press Dodik on his denial of Srebrenica genocide|url=http://ictj.org/news/columbia-must-press-dodik-his-denial-srebrenica-genocide|newspaper=International Center for Transitional Justice}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hodzic|first=Refik|title=Put the president in his place|url=http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2011/10/25/put-president-his-place|newspaper=Columbia Spectator|date=25 October 2011}}</ref> Protests also took place while the speech was in progress.<ref>{{cite news|last=Roth|first=Sammy|title=Balkan politician draws protesters at Low speech|url=http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2011/10/26/balkan-politician-draws-protesters-low-library-speech|newspaper=Columbia Spectator|date=26 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230193732/http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2011/10/26/balkan-politician-draws-protesters-low-library-speech|archivedate=30 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041c\u0430\u043b\u044b\u0448\u0435\u0432 \u0438 \u041c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043a.jpg|thumb|Dodik with Dmitry Malyshev in August 2012.]]\nIn October 2012, Dodik proposed that Bosnia and Herzegovina's unified armed forces be abolished.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2012/10/20/feature-01 |title=Archived copy |access-date=21 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022085229/http://setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2012/10/20/feature-01 |archive-date=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 3 November 2012, Dodik announced that the government of Republika Srpska would donate an undisclosed amount to help pay for the renovation of [[Patriarch Irinej of Serbia|Serbian Orthodox Patriarch Irinej]]'s old residence in Belgrade. Irinej commented that \"this is a great opportunity to show practically the unity of the Serbian people and Serbian church outside our borders.\" Serb bloggers expressed \"disagreement with both at a time of severe economic crisis and hardship\" followed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Djurovic|first=Katica|title=Serbian patriarch's residency renovation raises eyebrows|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/blogreview/2012/11/03/blog-03|newspaper=Southeast European Times|date=3 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Milorad Dodik and Vladimir Putin (2018-09-30) 01.jpg|thumb|<center>Dodik with [[Vladimir Putin]]<br />[[Sochi]], [[Russia]], 30 September 2018.</center>]]\n\nOn 13 November 2012, [[Valentin Inzko]], the [[High Representative for Bosnia and Herzegovina]], cited Dodik as \"the most frequent, although certainly not the sole, proponent of [Bosnian] state dissolution\" in a report to the [[UN Security Council]]. He added that \"the most recent and troubling of these is an initiative sent by the president to the Republika Srpska National Assembly attempting to create conditions that would unilaterally force the dissolution of the Armed Forces of Bosnia and Herzegovina.\" [[Vitaly Churkin]], Russian Representative to the United Nations, defended Dodik and blamed the Bosniaks for the tension.<ref>{{cite news|last=Charbonneau|first=Louis|title=EU says Bosnian Serbs seek to undermine peace deal|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/13/us-bosnia-un-idUSBRE8AC13F20121113|newspaper=Reuters|date=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, German state prosecution implicated Dodik and his son in a corruption case involving the [[Hypo Alpe-Adria-Bank International]]. The investigation concerned \"several criminal offenses, including falsifying of documents, faking financial and business reports and fraud.\" The judicial system of Bosnia and Herzegovina initially investigated the case following a complaint filing, but \"political pressures soon stopped the judicial bodies and the police in the RS.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=German prosecution investigates RS president for corruption|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2012&mm=11&dd=15&nav_id=83171|newspaper=B92|date=15 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203045210/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2012&mm=11&dd=15&nav_id=83171|archivedate=3 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to Domagoj Margeti\u0107, a Croatian journalist, Dodik had bribed and threatened him in order to not link him to the Hypo Group Alpe Adria affair story.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jukic|first=Elvira M.|title=Bosnian Serb Chief Tried to Bribe Me, Reporter Says|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/croatian-journalist-accused-dodik-of-bribe-attempt|newspaper=Balkan Insight|date=24 November 2012}}</ref> On 26 November 2012, High Representative in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Valentin Inzko, confirmed that there was no investigation against President of Republika Srpska Milorad Dodik and his family in Germany or Austria.<ref>Press Online: Incko: Nema istrage protiv Dodika {{cite web |url=http://pressrs.ba/sr/vesti/vesti_dana/story/27813/Incko%3A+Nema+istrage+protiv+Dodika!.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203132635/http://pressrs.ba/sr/vesti/vesti_dana/story/27813/Incko%3A+Nema+istrage+protiv+Dodika!.html |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 2017, the U.S. Department of the Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) imposed sanctions on Milorad Dodik pursuant to Executive Order 13304 and due to his role in defying the Constitutional Court of Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite news|title=Treasury Sanctions Republika Srpska Official for Actively Obstructing The Dayton Accords|url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/jl0708.aspx|work=[[Office of Foreign Assets Control|U.S. Department of the Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC)]]|date=1 January 2017}}</ref> \"By obstructing the Dayton Accords, Milorad Dodik poses a significant threat to the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Bosnia and Herzegovina,\" said John E. Smith, Acting OFAC Director.  \"Today's action underscores the U.S. commitment to the Dayton Accords and supports international efforts for the country's continued European integration.\" Any property of Mr. Milorad Dodik within the U.S. jurisdiction is to be blocked and U.S. persons, individuals or companies, are prohibited in to engage in business transactions with him.\n\nOn October 7, 2018, Dodik was elected to Bosnia's three-person Presidency, representing the Serbs, after ousting incumbent Bosnian Serb President [[Mladen Ivani\u0107]].<ref>https://www.ksl.com/article/46401834/pro-russian-serb-leader-wins-seat-in-bosnias-presidency</ref><ref>https://www.couriermail.com.au/news/breaking-news/bosnians-vote-in-divisive-general-election/news-story/fbea52ef8353ba316e937a1afc791236</ref>\n\n== Views ==\n=== Opinions on Tuzla and Markale ===\nIn 2009, Dodik stated that the [[Tuzla massacre]] was staged and questioned the [[Markale massacres]] at Sarajevo. The [[Tuzla]] municipality filed charges against Dodik over these statements. The city of [[Sarajevo]] filed criminal charges against Dodik for abuse of power, and inciting ethnic, racial and religious hatred.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sarajevo files charges against RS's Dodik|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/newsbriefs/2009/10/07/nb-06|newspaper=Southeast European Times|date=7 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Office of the High Representative]] said Dodik denied the war crimes committed and stated that \"When such skewed facts come from an official in a position of high responsibility, an official who is obliged to uphold the Dayton Peace Accords and cooperate with the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia|Hague Tribunal]], then they are particularly irresponsible and undermine not only the institutions responsible for upholding the rule of law, but the credibility of the individual himself\".<ref>{{cite news|title=OHR slams Dodik statements|url=http://www6.b92.net/eng/news/region-article.php?yyyy=2009&mm=09&dd=16&nav_id=61796|newspaper=B92|date=16 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Srebrenica genocide opinion ===\nOn 21 April 2010, the government of Dodik initiated a revision of the 2004 report saying that the numbers of killed were exaggerated and the report was manipulated by a former peace envoy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Srebrenica was not genocide: Bosnian Serb leader |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20100427-srebrenica-was-not-genocide-bosnian-serb-leader |newspaper=France 24 |date=27 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717064036/http://www.france24.com/en/20100427-srebrenica-was-not-genocide-bosnian-serb-leader |archivedate=17 July 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLDE63K0E2|title= Envoy slams Bosnia Serbs for questioning Srebrenica|work=Reuters|accessdate= 21 April 2010}}</ref> The [[Office of the High Representative]] responded and stated that: \"The Republika Srpska government should reconsider its conclusions and align itself with the facts and legal requirements and act accordingly, rather than inflicting emotional distress on the survivors, torture history and denigrate the public image of the country\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ohr.int/ohr-dept/presso/pressr/default.asp?content_id=44835 |title=RS Government Special Session A Distasteful Attempt to Question Genocide |publisher=OHR |accessdate=21 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318084354/http://www.ohr.int/ohr-dept/presso/pressr/default.asp?content_id=44835 |archivedate=18 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 July 2010, at the 15th anniversary of the [[Srebrenica massacre]], Dodik declared that he acknowledges the killings that happened on the site, but does not regard what happened at Srebrenica as [[genocide]], differing from the conclusions of the [[ICTY]] and of the [[International Court of Justice]]. \"If a genocide happened then it was committed against Serb people of this region where women, children and the elderly were killed en masse,\" Dodik said, in reference to eastern Bosnia.<ref>[http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/srebrenica-massacre-not-genocide-20100713-1083q.html Srebrenica massacre 'not genocide'], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]/[[Agence France Presse]]'', 13 July 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Arslanagic|first=Sabina|title=Dodik Again Denies Srebrenica Genocide|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/dodik-slams-international-community-for-referring-to-srebrenica-massacre-as-genocide|newspaper=Balkan Insight|date=3 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Peace Implementation Council Steering Board Communiqu\u00e9|url=http://www.ohr.int/pic/default.asp?content_id=45573|newspaper=Office of the High Representative|date=1 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207141408/http://www.ohr.int/pic/default.asp?content_id=45573|archivedate=7 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107 ===\nIn March 2016, he named a student dormitory in [[Pale, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Pale]] in honor of the wartime Serb leader [[Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/21/student-dorm-named-after-war-crimes-suspect-radovan-karadzic|title=Student dorm named after war crimes suspect Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 March 2014|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref> The event took place only a few days before Karad\u017ei\u0107 was convicted for war crimes by the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-warcrimes-bosnia-karadzic-idUSKCN0WP2ZW|title=Karadzic guilty of Bosnia genocide, jailed for 40 years|work=Reuters|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic has been found guilty of genocide|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21695737-yugoslavia-tribunal-sentences-its-biggest-fish-it-has-failed-reconcile-bosnia-former|accessdate=26 March 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|date=24 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is married to Snje\u017eana Dodik, with whom he has two children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bideleux |first1=Robert |last2=Jeffries |first2=Ian |title=The Balkans: A Post-Communist History |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-415-22962-3 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/balkanspostcommu0000bide }}\n*{{cite book|last=Eralp |first=Do\u011fa U. |title=Politics of the European Union in Bosnia-Herzegovina: Between Conflict and Democracy |publisher=Lexington Books |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-7391-4945-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Petersen |first=Roger D. |title=Western Intervention in the Balkans: The Strategic Use of Emotion in Conflict |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-107-01066-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=\u0160edo |first=Jakub |year=2013 |chapter=The party system of Bosnia and Herzegovina |editor-last1=Stojarov\u00e1 |editor-first1=Vera |editor-last2=Emerson |editor-first2=Peter |title=Party Politics in the Western Balkans |location=New York |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-23585-7 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Milorad Dodik}}\n*[http://www.predsjednikrs.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=81&Itemid=141&lang=en Official biography]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060220071944/http://www.snsd.org/ SNSD Official Website]\n*[http://www.predsjednikrs.net/ President of the Republic Milorad Dodik]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gojko Kli\u010dkovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Prime Ministers of Republika Srpska|Prime Minister of Republika Srpska]]|years=1998\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mladen Ivani\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pero Bukejlovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Prime Ministers of Republika Srpska|Prime Minister of Republika Srpska]]|years=2006\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Anton Kasipovi\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rajko Kuzmanovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[ President of Republika Srpska]]|years=2010\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[\u017deljka Cvijanovi\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef||before=[[Bakir Izetbegovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chairman of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft||after=[[\u017deljko Kom\u0161i\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mladen Ivani\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina#Serb members|Serb Member of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Bosnian President}}\n{{Presidents of Republika Srpska}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Republika Srpska}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dodik, Milorad}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:People from Banja Luka]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime ministers of Republika Srpska]]\n[[Category:Politicians of Republika Srpska]]\n[[Category:Alliance of Independent Social Democrats politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Belgrade Faculty of Political Science alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:KK Igokea]]\n[[Category:Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "46.114.2.85", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milorad_Dodik"}
