{"title_page": "Keirle House", "text_new": "{{Infobox historic site\n| name = Keirle House\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| locmapin = Nebraska\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|20|05|N|95|57|40|W|display=inline,title}}\n| location = [[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n| area =\n| built = 1905<ref name=\"OMAL Keirle\"/>\n| architect =\n| architecture = Eclectic Style\n| governing_body =\n| owner =\n| designation1 = Omaha Landmark\n| designation1_date = July 15, 1997<ref name=\"OMAL Keirle\"/>\n| designation1_number =\n}}\n\nThe '''Keirle House''' is located at 3017 Mormon Street in the [[Florence, Nebraska|Florence]] neighborhood of [[North Omaha]], [[Nebraska]]. Built in 1905 in the [[classic box]] style popular in the [[Midwest]], the Keirle House was designated an [[Omaha Landmark]] in 1997.<ref name=\"OMAL Keirle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofomaha.org/planning/landmarks/alphabetical-listing/keirle-house|title=Keirle House|publisher=City of Omaha \u2014 Landmarks Heritage Preservation Commission|accessdate=2012-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==About==\nThe Keirle House was built by the founder and owner of the Keirle Ice Company, which cut its ice from the Florence Water Works and shipped them across the Midwest for top price. Its four bedrooms occupy a small estate in the middle of Florence.\n\nThe Florence Historical Foundation restored this house in 1996 after the death of Maude Keirle, the last member of the only family that ever lived there. Built with a variety of styles, the Keirle House is a Midwest \"classic box\" with Queen Anne and classical revival details. It was built to face the town square of [[Winter Quarters, Nebraska|Winter Quarters]], which the Mormons originally laid out in 1846.<ref name=\"OMAL Keirle\"/>\n\nUntil February 2011, the House previously served as offices for the [[Uta Halee Girls Village]] executive offices.<ref name=OWH>{{cite news|title=Old House May Lose Landmark Tag |url=http://www.omaha.com/article/20111107/NEWS01/711079885 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130193125/http://www.omaha.com/article/20111107/NEWS01/711079885 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 30, 2013 |accessdate=10 November 2011 |newspaper=Omaha World-Herald Newspaper, Omaha, NE, USA |date=November 7, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 9, 2011, Omaha's Landmarks Heritage Preservation Commission voted to delay a vote indefinitely on removing the House's historic landmark designation.<ref name=\"OWH Article 2\">{{cite news|title=Florence Home Still A Landmark, For Now|newspaper=The Omaha World-Herald Newspaper, Omaha, NE, USA|date=November 10, 2011}}</ref>  The owners of the home had requested the designation be removed to ease the property's sale.\n\nOn March 9, 2012, the Keirle House was purchased by Robert and Kristina Mitchell for the purchase price of $110,000.  Robert and Kristina use the property to store cars.  The house is kept up, but is empty. The House remains on Omaha's Landmarks Heritage Preservation Commission registry.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.historicflorence.org/images/HistoricHomes/KeirleHouse-585x394.jpg Modern photo] of the Keirle House.\n\n{{Florence}}\n{{Omaha Landmark houses}}\n{{NRHP Omaha}}\n\n[[Category:Houses in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in North Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Omaha Landmarks]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1905]]\n\n\n{{Omaha-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox historic site\n| name = Keirle House\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| locmapin = Nebraska\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|20|05|N|95|57|40|W|display=inline,title}}\n| location = [[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n| area =\n| built = 1905<ref name=\"OMAL Keirle\"/>\n| architect =\n| architecture = Eclectic Style\n| governing_body =\n| owner =\n| designation1 = Omaha Landmark\n| designation1_date = July 15, 1997<ref name=\"OMAL Keirle\"/>\n| designation1_number =\n}}\n\nThe '''Keirle House''' is located at 3017 Mormon Street in the [[Florence, Nebraska|Florence]] neighborhood of [[North Omaha]], [[Nebraska]]. Built in 1905 in the [[classic box]] style popular in the [[Midwest]], the Keirle House was designated an [[Omaha Landmark]] in 1997.<ref name=\"OMAL Keirle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofomaha.org/planning/landmarks/alphabetical-listing/keirle-house|title=Keirle House|publisher=City of Omaha \u2014 Landmarks Heritage Preservation Commission|accessdate=2012-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==About==\nThe Keirle House was built by the founder and owner of the Keirle Ice Company, which cut its ice from the Florence Water Works and shipped them across the Midwest for top price. Its four bedrooms occupy a small estate in the middle of Florence.\n\nThe Florence Historical Foundation restored this house in 1996 after the death of Maude Keirle, the last member of the only family that ever lived there. Built with a variety of styles, the Keirle House is a Midwest \"classic box\" with Queen Anne and classical revival details. It was built to face the town square of [[Winter Quarters, Nebraska|Winter Quarters]], which the Mormons originally laid out in 1846.<ref name=\"OMAL Keirle\"/>\n\nUntil February 2011, the House previously served as offices for the [[Uta Halee Girls Village]] executive offices.<ref name=OWH>{{cite news|title=Old House May Lose Landmark Tag |url=http://www.omaha.com/article/20111107/NEWS01/711079885 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130193125/http://www.omaha.com/article/20111107/NEWS01/711079885 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 30, 2013 |accessdate=10 November 2011 |newspaper=Omaha World-Herald Newspaper, Omaha, NE, USA |date=November 7, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 9, 2011, Omaha's Landmarks Heritage Preservation Commission voted to delay a vote indefinitely on removing the House's historic landmark designation.<ref name=\"OWH Article 2\">{{cite news|title=Florence Home Still A Landmark, For Now|newspaper=The Omaha World-Herald Newspaper, Omaha, NE, USA|date=November 10, 2011}}</ref>  The owners of the home had requested the designation be removed to ease the property's sale.\n\nOn March 9, 2012, the Keirle House was purchased by Robert and Kristina Mitchell for the purchase price of $110,000.  Robert and Kristina will use the house as their primary residence.  The House remains on Omaha's Landmarks Heritage Preservation Commission registry.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.historicflorence.org/images/HistoricHomes/KeirleHouse-585x394.jpg Modern photo] of the Keirle House.\n\n{{Florence}}\n{{Omaha Landmark houses}}\n{{NRHP Omaha}}\n\n[[Category:Houses in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in North Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Omaha Landmarks]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1905]]\n\n\n{{Omaha-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Afmgreentea", "label": "safe", "comment": "The owners of the house DO NOT use the property as their primary residence.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keirle_House"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt", "text_new": "{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS ''Theodore Roosevelt''}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic on board USS ''Theodore Roosevelt''\n| image           = CVN-71-2019-10-01-1.jpg\n| caption         = USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' in October 2019\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n| first_case      = {{ship|USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|2}}\n| arrival_date    = 24 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 1\n| confirmed_cases = 660<ref name=\"navy.status\">{{Cite web|url=https://navylive.dodlive.mil/2020/03/15/u-s-navy-covid-19-updates/|title=U.S. Navy COVID-19 Updates|website=Navy Live}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARSCoV-2), the cause of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], was detected on the aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} in March 2020 while she was at sea. Affected crew members were evacuated and the ship was ordered to Guam. The captain, [[Brett Crozier]], wanted most of the crew to be removed from the ship to prevent the spread of the disease, but his superiors balked. After several days Crozier e-mailed three of his superior officers and seven other Navy Captains, outlining a plan for the ship to be largely evacuated because the virus could not be contained on board. The letter leaked to the press, and the next day the Navy ordered most of the crew to be taken ashore, but the captain was relieved of command by Acting Secretary of the Navy [[Thomas Modly]]. Modly's order was controversial, and his later speech to the crew aboard the ''Roosevelt'' was criticized. Modly resigned a few days later. By mid-April hundreds of crew members including Crozier had tested positive for the virus, and one had died.\n\n==Timeline==\nIn spring 2020, the [[United States Navy]] aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|2}} was on deployment in the Pacific.\n\n===March===\nOn 5 March, the ship made a four-day-long port call at [[Da Nang]], Vietnam. On the last night some sailors stayed at a hotel where two people had tested positive for [[COVID-19]], a coronavirus disease identified as the cause of an outbreak of respiratory illness. Upon learning this, the crew were ordered back to the ship and the sailors who had stayed at the hotel were isolated.<ref name = losses/> The ship departed on 9 March.<ref name=doTimeline>{{cite web |last1=Peniston |first1=Bradley |title=The Battle of USS Theodore Roosevelt: a Timeline |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/04/timeline-battle-uss-theodore-roosevelt/164408/ |website=Defense One |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200411135930/https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/04/timeline-battle-uss-theodore-roosevelt/164408/ |archivedate=11 April 2020 |date=13 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Over the next weeks the ship's medical team monitored the crew for any signs of infection.<ref name = losses/> The sailors associated with the hotel visit were later tested negative.<ref name=\"flightcrew\">{{cite web |url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2020/04/15/covid-19-outbreak-on-theodore-roosevelt-sparked-by-flight-crews-officials-believe/ |title=COVID-19 outbreak on Theodore Roosevelt sparked by flight crews, officials believe |work=Navy Times |last=Simkin |first=J.D. |date=16 April 2020 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the first sailor tested positive.<ref name=doTimeline/> By 24 March, three further sailors of the flightcrew aboard had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/24/coronavirus-3-sailors-test-positive-military-readiness-affected/2910165001/ |title=Three sailors from USS Theodore Roosevelt have coronavirus, raising concerns about pandemic's strain on military |work=USA Today |last=Vanden Brook |first=Tom|authorlink=Tom Vanden Brook|date=24 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"flightcrew\" />\n\nWithin a few days, that number climbed to \"dozens.\" ''Theodore Roosevelt'' was ordered to [[Guam]] and docked on 27 March 2020.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 />\n\nOn 30 March, the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]], sent an [[Classified information in the United States#Unclassified|unclassified email]] to three admirals in his chain of command, including the commander of the [[United States Pacific Fleet]] and Adm. [[Stuart P. Baker|Baker]], his immediate superior. The memo outlined the coronavirus outbreak aboard the ship and recommended that he be given permission to evacuate all non-essential sailors, quarantine known COVID-19 cases, and sanitize the ship. Seven captains - five aboard the ''Roosevelt'' and two who are assistants to higher admirals - were copied on the e-mail.<ref name=WaPoTickTock>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/how-an-outbreak-on-the-uss-roosevelt-became-a-defining-moment-for-the-us-military/2020/04/16/2735f85c-7f24-11ea-8de7-9fdff6d5d83e_story.html How an outbreak on the USS Roosevelt became a defining moment for the U.S. military]. ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 16 April 2020</ref> <ref name = Cohn>{{Cite news |last=Cohn |first=Lindsay |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/05/this-is-what-was-so-unusual-about-us-navy-making-captain-brett-crozier-step-down/ |title=This is what was so unusual about the U.S. Navy making Captain Brett Crozier step down\u2014Members of the military can face multiple, sometimes competing, loyalties |access-date=6 April 2020 |work=The Washington Post |last2=Friend |first2=Alice |last3=Golby |first3=Jim}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, over 100 sailors tested positive.<ref name=Schogol>{{cite web |last1=Schogol |first1=Jeff |title=Navy captain says COVID-19 is spreading through his aircraft carrier so rapidly that most of the crew needs to get off |url=https://taskandpurpose.com/news/uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus-isolation |website=Task & Purpose |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406231152/https://taskandpurpose.com/news/uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus-isolation |archivedate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The letter was leaked to the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]],'' which published it.<ref name = Gafni>{{cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Exclusive-Captain-of-aircraft-carrier-with-15167883.php |title=Exclusive: Captain of aircraft carrier with growing coronavirus outbreak pleads for help from Navy|last1=Gafni|first1=Matthias |last2=Garofoli|first2=Joe |date=31 March 2020|work=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, the Navy ordered the aircraft carrier largely evacuated, with a skeleton crew to remain aboard the vessel to maintain the nuclear reactor, the fire-fighting equipment, the ship's galley, and a disinfection crew.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 >{{cite news|last=Peniston|first=Bradley |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/03/us-navy-evacuating-aircraft-carrier-infected-coronavirus/164254/?oref=d-channelriver |title=US Navy Evacuating Aircraft Carrier Infected by Coronavirus|work=Defense One|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]] relieved Crozier of his command.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> According to Modly, Crozier didn't inform his [[Carrier Strike Group 9|superior on the ship]] about sending the letter, and Modly conferred with Crozier's [[chain of command]].<ref name=Gallagher>{{cite web |last1=Gallagher |first1=Sean |title=Aircraft carrier captain lost his command because of \u201cCatch-22\u201d COVID-19 dilemma |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/04/aircraft-carrier-captain-lost-his-command-because-of-catch-22-covid-19-dilemma/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407231021/https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/04/aircraft-carrier-captain-lost-his-command-because-of-catch-22-covid-19-dilemma/ |archivedate=7 April 2020 |language=en-us |date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, this was not true, because Crozier had sent the letter directly to Rear Admiral Stuart Baker, Commander, [[Carrier Strike Group 9]].<ref name=WaPoTickTock/>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, the Navy confirmed that 155 sailors had been infected and that 1,500 sailors had been removed from the ship, a lower number than the Navy had projected several days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/sailors-uss-teddy-roosevelt-positive-covid-19-navy |title=155 sailors on USS Theodore Roosevelt test positive for coronavirus, 42 percent of all Navy infections |work=Fox News |last=Ruiz |first=Michael |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Modly traveled to Guam to visit the ship in person.<ref name=\"trip\">{{cite news |title=Blistering Reprimand from Navy Secretary |date=7 April 2020 |author=Helene Cooper |work=[[The New York Times]] |page=A11}}</ref> He made a speech to the crew over the ship's [[public address system]], strongly criticizing Crozier. The transcript and an audio recording of Modly's speech were subsequently leaked to the media.<ref name = Larison/> Later that day, Modly apologized for the comment.<ref name = Casiano>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/acting-navy-secretary-uss-theodore-roosevelt-speech-calls-for-his-firing |title=Trump hints that he may get involved in Navy episode as Modly issues apology|last1=Casiano|first1=Louis |last2=Aaro|first2=David |date=7 April 2020|work=Fox News|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> He resigned from his post the following day.\n\nOn 7 April, the Navy said 61% of ''Theodore Roosevelt''{{'}}s crew had been tested for COVID-19 and 173 members had tested positive, including Captain Crozier. None were hospitalized. Two thousand sailors \u2014 just under half the total crew \u2014 had been moved ashore.<ref name=\"Guardian20200407\">{{cite news |last1=Borger|first1=Julian |last2=|first2=|title=US navy official apologises for calling captain behind coronavirus memo 'naive or stupid' |date=7 April 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/06/navy-coronavirus-ship-theodore-roosevelt-thomas-modly |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, the Navy reported that 416 crew members had tested positive for the virus, and that one quarantined sailor was hospitalized in intensive care after being found unconscious in his quarantine quarters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/uss-theodore-roosevelt-sailor-with-coronavirus-taken-to-icu-2020-4 |title=A USS Theodore Roosevelt sailor with coronavirus was taken to the ICU as the number of cases on the aircraft carrier rises|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|date=April 9, 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, it was reported that more than 90% of the crew had been tested for the coronavirus, and 550 crew members had tested positive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/100-new-coronavirus-cases-uss-theodore-roosevelt-550-total-2020-4 |title=100 more sailors from the USS Theodore Roosevelt have tested positive for coronavirus, making up 75% of the Navy's total cases worldwide|last=Holmes|first=Aaron|date=11 April 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=McNamara |first1=Audrey |title=Coronavirus cases on USS Theodore Roosevelt spike to 550|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-cases-on-uss-theodore-roosevelt-spike-to-550-2020-04-11/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=CBS |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 12 April, 585 crew members had tested positive.<ref name = dies/>\n\nOn 13 April, the hospitalized sailor died.<ref name = dies>politico.com: [https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/13/sailor-uss-roosevelt-dies-coronavirus-183164 ''Sailor from USS Theodore Roosevelt dies of coronavirus'']</ref>\n\nAs of 16 April, more than 4,000 of the 4,500 member crew had been removed from the ship.<ref name=WaPoTickTock/> 655 crew members had tested positive. Six were in the hospital<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/493192-fired-captain-sent-memo-to-fewer-people-than-former-navy-head-alleged-report |title=Fired captain sent memo to fewer people than former Navy head alleged: report|last=Kheel|first=Rebecca |date=16 April 2020|work=The Hill|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> including 5 in intensive care. About 60% of the people who tested positive [[asymptomatic|did not have symptoms]].<ref name=phil>{{cite web |author1=Phil Stewart, Idrees Ali |title=Coronavirus clue? Most cases aboard U.S. aircraft carrier are symptom-free |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-military-sympt/coronavirus-clue-most-cases-aboard-u-s-aircraft-carrier-are-symptom-free-idUSKCN21Y2GB |website=[[Reuters]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200417054516/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-military-sympt/coronavirus-clue-most-cases-aboard-u-s-aircraft-carrier-are-symptom-free-idUSKCN21Y2GB |archivedate=17 April 2020 |language=en |date=16 April 2020 |quote=The findings are of enormous interest because the proportion of people who are asymptomatic is just simply not known |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Crozier's letter==\n[[File:Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg|thumb|Ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]]]]\nWhen the ship arrived in Guam on 26 March the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]], wanted to have most of the crew immediately taken ashore, saying it was impossible to prevent the spread of the virus in the close quarters of the ship. Rear Adm. [[Stuart P. Baker]], who was the commanding officer of [[Carrier Strike Group 9]] and thus Crozier's immediate superior, disagreed, feeling such an action was impractical and too drastic.<ref name = losses>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/coronavirus-roosevelt-carrier-crozier.html?campaign_id=60&emc=edit_na_20200413&instance_id=0&nl=breaking-news&ref=cta&regi_id=16153474&segment_id=24971&user_id=e9848bda5d7546386411f6e2fbdaf95e|title=\u2018There Will Be Losses\u2019: How a Captain\u2019s Plea Exposed a Rift in the Military|date=13 April 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Crozier sent an email to communicate the status of his ship and its crew, saying it was not possible to observe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]/Navy<ref>{{cite web |title=Restriction of Movement (ROM) guidance. Navy mitigation measures in response to Novel Coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.public.navy.mil/bupers-npc/reference/messages/Documents/NAVADMINS/NAV2020/NAV20083.txt |publisher=NAVADMIN |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> recommendations for individual quarantine or [[social distancing]] aboard the carrier. Crozier referred to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on Diamond Princess|viral spread on the less crowded cruise ship ''Diamond Princess'']] as an example of [[Basic reproduction number|how quickly a virus can spread]] on a crowded vessel.<ref name = Gafni/><ref name=\"documentcloud\">{{cite web|url=https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/6821571/TR-COVID-19-Assistance-Request.pdf |date=29 March 2020|title=Request for assistance in response to COVID-19 pandemic |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Voltaire>{{cite web |title=Request of assistance in response to pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt, by Captain Brett E. Crozier (text) |url=https://www.voltairenet.org/article209667.html |website=Voltaire Network |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The letter provided his superiors with options, but recommended most<!--90%--> of the crew's evacuation, keeping only enough crew on board to maintain the nuclear reactor, provide security, and to [[Disinfection|sanitize the ship]]. The e-mail was sent to three superior officers in his chain of command, including his direct superior, Rear Admiral Baker, and was copied to seven captains - five of whom were aboard the Roosevelt, the other two of whom were executive assistants to the admirals.<ref name=USNI>[https://blog.usni.org/posts/2020/04/17/return-crozier-to-the-roosevelt-restore-faith-in-the-navy Return Crozier to the Roosevelt, Restore Faith in the Navy]. [[Guy Snodgrass]], [[United States Naval Institute]]. April 17, 2020</ref><ref name=WaPoTickTock/><ref name = Cohn/><ref name = losses/> The letter was leaked to the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', which published it the next day.<ref name = Gafni/>\n\n==Relieving Crozier of command and aftermath==\nOn 2 April, acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]] relieved Crozier of his command for sending the request for assistance over non-secure email to a \"broad array of people\" rather than up the chain of command, adding that Crozier \"allowed the complexity of the challenge of the COVID breakout on the ship to overwhelm his ability to act professionally\". Crozier will remain in the Navy and retain his rank.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> As Crozier disembarked, sailors were seen chanting \"Cap-tain Cro-zier\" in a video posted to [[Twitter]] captioned \"Wrongfully relieved of command but did right by the sailors.\"<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[NBC News]] |title=Videos show sailors cheering Navy captain relieved of command after raising alarm on coronavirus |date=3 April 2020 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/videos-show-sailors-cheering-navy-captain-relieved-command-after-raising-n1175946 |first=Janelle |last=Griffith}}</ref>\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?470922-1/us-navy-fires-captain-raised-alarm-coronavirus-aircraft-carrier U.S. Department of Defense briefing with Navy Secretary Modly in which he announces the relief of Capt. Crozier from his duty as the captain of the ''Theodore Roosevelt'', April 2, 2020], [[C-SPAN]]}} Modly claimed that  Crozier had sent a \"blast out email to anybody who he knows about the situation\" and even \"copied [the email] to 20 or 30 other people.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/uss-theodore-roosevelt-commander-fired-after-unclassified-email-2020-4|title='Not acceptable': Navy claims it fired the captain dealing with coronavirus outbreak for sending 'blast out' email to at least 20 people with 'unclassified' system|last=Choi|first=David|date=April 2, 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' subsequently obtained the e-mail and found that it had been sent to only 10 people, all Navy admirals or captains.<ref name=\"WaPoTickTock\"/>\n\nReaction to Crozier's dismissal was mixed. A ''Wall Street Journal'' story reported that on \"Capitol Hill and inside the Pentagon, lawmakers and officials reacted with confusion and anger over the dismissal\" of Crozier.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/captain-fired-by-navy-gets-rousing-farewell-from-sailors-11585933116?mod=hp_lista_pos2 |title=Captain Fired by Navy Gets Rousing Farewell from Sailors |last=Youssef |first=Nancy A. |last2=Lubold |first2=Gordon |date=3 April 2020 |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> A joint statement from four Democrats on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|House Armed Services Committee]], including the committee chair, [[Adam Smith (politician)|Representative Adam Smith (D-WA)]], criticized Crozier's conduct, saying that \"Captain Crozier was justifiably concerned about the health and safety of his crew, but he did not handle the immense pressure appropriately. However, relieving him of his command is an overreaction.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Welna |first1=David |title=After Outcry Over Navy Captain Relieved Of Command, Assurances He Won't Be Expelled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/03/826920834/after-outcry-over-navy-captain-relieved-of-command-assurances-he-wont-be-expelle |website=npr.org |publisher=National Public Radio, Inc.}}</ref> [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] also criticized Crozier's letter on 4 April saying that it was \"not appropriate.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/04/trump-says-navy-captain-letter-asking-for-help-on-coronavirus-stricken-ship-was-terrible.html |title=Trump says Navy captain letter asking for help on coronavirus-stricken ship 'was terrible' |last=Feuer|first=William |date=4 April 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nModly, U.S. Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Michael M. Gilday|Michael Gilday]] each defended the decision to remove Crozier,<ref name=croziergone>{{cite web |first=Rebecca |last=Kheel |title=Aircraft carrier captain removed from duty after pleading for help with coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/490892-aircraft-carrier-captain-to-be-removed-from-duty-after-pleading-for-help-with |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=2020-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Devan |last=Cole |title=Esper defends removing USS Theodore Roosevelt commander who sounded alarm over coronavirus |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/politics/mark-esper-uss-theodore-roosevelt-defends-removal-cnntv/index.html |work=CNN |date=2020-04-05 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> although Gilday and Gen. [[Mark A. Milley]], the [[chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], had earlier advised Modly not to do it until a Navy investigation into the matter had been completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/15/us/politics/coronavirus-navy-roosevelt-crozier.html?campaign_id=9&emc=edit_NN_p_20200416&instance_id=17682&nl=morning-briefing&regi_id=16153474&section=topNews&segment_id=25289&te=1&user_id=e9848bda5d7546386411f6e2fbdaf95e|title=Navy May Reinstate Fired Captain to Command of Roosevelt|date=April 16, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Modly added that there was no White House pressure when the decision was made to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone />\n\nOn 6 April Modly traveled {{convert|8,000|mi}}<ref name=\"trip\"/> to Guam on a Navy executive jet; the trip was later reported to have cost taxpayers at least $243,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2020/04/08/trip-guam-center-top-navy-officials-resignation-cost-taxpayers-least-243000/?utm_campaign=wp_post_most&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&wpisrc=nl_most|title=Trip to Guam at center of top Navy official\u2019s resignation cost taxpayers over $243,000|last=Lamothe|first=Dan|date=April 8, 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> He visited the ship in person and made a speech to the crew over the ship's [[public address system]]. He began by blaming the Chinese government for worsening the outbreak by not telling how bad the disease was. He continued by strongly criticizing Crozier, saying he was \"too na\u00efve or too stupid to be a commanding officer,\" if he did not realize that the letter would be leaked to the media.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ismay |first1=John |last2=Ziezulewicz |first2=Geoff |title=Acting Navy Secretary Slams Fired Captain as 'Stupid' |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/magazine/modly-crozier-coronavirus.html |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Modly also scolded the ship's crew for cheering their captain as he left.<ref name=\"trip\"/>  The transcript and an audio recording of Modly's speech was subsequently leaked to the media.<ref name = Larison>{{cite news |last1=Larison |first1=Daniel |title=After Crozier Comments, Navy Secretary Modly Must Resign |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The American Conservative]] |url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/larison/modly-must-resign/ |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nModly's speech was widely criticized. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Tim Kaine]] stated \"It's deeply disappointing that he would deliver a speech on board a U.S. aircraft carrier suggesting that Captain Crozier might be 'stupid'.\" [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Elaine Luria]] called for the removal of Modly, with Luria, a Navy veteran, saying he was \"in no way fit\" to lead the Navy.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Navy morale dives after firing of virus-riddled ship's captain |url=https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/264591472/us-navy-morale-dives-after-firing-of-virus-riddled-ship-captain |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Big News Network.com |language=en}}</ref> Chairperson of the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Armed Services Committee's panel on military personnel]], [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Jackie Speier]] also criticized the trip.<ref name=\"ModlyCost\">{{cite news |last1=Brook |first1=Tom Vanden |title=Cost of Navy secretary's trip to Guam? $243,000, his job and isolation after coronavirus exposure |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/08/navy-secretary-trip-roosevelt-cost-243-000-leads-modly-ouster/2973486001/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Modly apologized for the comment.<ref name = Casiano/> The following day, he resigned his position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/acting-navy-secretary-resigns-in-wake-of-uss-roosevelt-11586287262 |title=Acting Navy Secretary Thomas Modly Resigns in Wake of USS Roosevelt Comments|last=Lubold|first=Gordon |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\nOn April 13 the first fatality among the sailors from the ship, a 41-year-old chief petty officer, was announced.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5823124/sailor-dies-coronavirus-identified/|title=First Active-Duty Navy Sailor to Die From COVID-19 Is Chief Petty Officer From Stricken Aircraft Carrier|date=16 April 2020|work=Associated Press|publisher=Time Magazine|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> He was the first active-duty member of the U.S. military to die of Covid-19.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-13/navy-sailor-from-uss-theodore-roosevelt-died-of-covid-19 \"Navy Sailor Dies in Guam After Virus Outbreak Aboard Carrier\"] Bloomberg.com</ref>\n\n==Number of confirmed cases==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 15 Apr, 16 Apr, 17 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y1= 3, 8, , , 33, , , , 93, , , , , 155, , 230, 286, 416, 447, 550, 585, 589, 615, 655, 660<!--data missing-->\n|y1Title=Confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|colors=#88aaaaaa,#88436DF4,#88F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|xType=date\n|xAxisFormat=%_d %b\n|showSymbols=1\n|type=stackedarea\n|x= 2020/03/23, 2020/03/24, 2020/03/27, 2020/03/31, 2020/04/05, 2020/04/07, 2020/04/08, 2020/04/09, 2020/04/10, 2020/04/11, 2020/04/12, 2020/04/13, 2020/04/15, 2020/04/16, 2020/04/17\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y3= 3, 8, 33, 93, 155, 230, 286, 416, 447, 550, 585, 589, 615, 655, 660<!--data missing-->\n|y2= ,,,593, 1500, 2037, 2588, 3170, 3284, 3673, 3724, 3922, 3958, 3919, 4059\n|y1= ,,,{{#expr:4865-593-93}},{{#expr:4865-1500-155}},{{#expr:4865-2037-230}},{{#expr:4865-2588-286}},{{#expr:4865-3170-416}},{{#expr:4865-3284-447}},{{#expr:4865-3673-550}},{{#expr:4865-3724-585}},{{#expr:4865-3922-589}}, {{#expr:4865-3958-615}}, {{#expr:4865-3919-655}} , {{#expr:4865-3920-660}}\n|y3Title=Confirmed cases\n|y2Title=Negative cases\n|y1Title=Untested\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania]]\n{{end div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Guam]]\n[[Category:2020 in military history]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by location|USS Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania|USS Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|USS Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Medicine in the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Water transport in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Guam]]\n[[Category:Disasters in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Health and transport]]\n[[Category:Health and military]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n[[Category:Military controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS ''Theodore Roosevelt''}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic on board USS ''Theodore Roosevelt''\n| image           = CVN-71-2019-10-01-1.jpg\n| caption         = USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' in October 2019\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n| first_case      = {{ship|USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|2}}\n| arrival_date    = 24 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 1\n| confirmed_cases = 660<ref name=\"navy.status\">{{Cite web|url=https://navylive.dodlive.mil/2020/03/15/u-s-navy-covid-19-updates/|title=U.S. Navy COVID-19 Updates|website=Navy Live}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARSCoV-2), the cause of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], was detected on the aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} in March 2020 while she was at sea. Affected crew members were evacuated and the ship was ordered to Guam. The captain, [[Brett Crozier]], wanted most of the crew to be removed from the ship to prevent the spread of the disease, but his superiors balked. After several days Crozier e-mailed three of his superior officers and seven other Navy Captains, outlining a plan for the ship to be largely evacuated because the virus could not be contained on board. The letter leaked to the press, and the next day the Navy ordered most of the crew to be taken ashore, but the captain was relieved of command by Acting Secretary of the Navy [[Thomas Modly]]. Modly's order was controversial, and his later speech to the crew aboard the ''Roosevelt'' was criticized. Modly resigned a few days later. By mid-April hundreds of crew members including Crozier had tested positive for the virus, and one had died.\n\n==Timeline==\nIn spring 2020, the [[United States Navy]] aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|2}} was on deployment in the Pacific.\n\n===March===\nOn 5 March, the ship made a four-day-long port call at [[Da Nang]], Vietnam. On the last night some sailors stayed at a hotel where two people had tested positive for [[COVID-19]], a coronavirus disease identified as the cause of an outbreak of respiratory illness. Upon learning this, the crew were ordered back to the ship and the sailors who had stayed at the hotel were isolated.<ref name = losses/> The ship departed on 9 March.<ref name=doTimeline>{{cite web |last1=Peniston |first1=Bradley |title=The Battle of USS Theodore Roosevelt: a Timeline |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/04/timeline-battle-uss-theodore-roosevelt/164408/ |website=Defense One |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200411135930/https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/04/timeline-battle-uss-theodore-roosevelt/164408/ |archivedate=11 April 2020 |date=13 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Over the next weeks the ship's medical team monitored the crew for any signs of infection.<ref name = losses/> The sailors associated with the hotel visit were later tested negative.<ref name=\"flightcrew\">{{cite web |url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2020/04/15/covid-19-outbreak-on-theodore-roosevelt-sparked-by-flight-crews-officials-believe/ |title=COVID-19 outbreak on Theodore Roosevelt sparked by flight crews, officials believe |work=Navy Times |last=Simkin |first=J.D. |date=16 April 2020 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the first sailor tested positive.<ref name=doTimeline/> By 24 March, three further sailors of the flightcrew aboard had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/24/coronavirus-3-sailors-test-positive-military-readiness-affected/2910165001/ |title=Three sailors from USS Theodore Roosevelt have coronavirus, raising concerns about pandemic's strain on military |work=USA Today |last=Vanden Brook |first=Tom|authorlink=Tom Vanden Brook|date=24 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"flightcrew\" />\n\nWithin a few days, that number climbed to \"dozens.\" ''Theodore Roosevelt'' was ordered to [[Guam]] and docked on 27 March 2020.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 />\n\nOn 30 March, the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]], sent an [[Classified information in the United States#Unclassified|unclassified email]] to three admirals in his chain of command, including the commander of the [[United States Pacific Fleet]] and Adm. [[Stuart P. Baker|Baker]], his immediate superior. The memo outlined the coronavirus outbreak aboard the ship and recommended that he be given permission to evacuate all non-essential sailors, quarantine known COVID-19 cases, and sanitize the ship. Seven captains - five aboard the ''Roosevelt'' and two who are assistants to higher admirals - were copied on the e-mail.<ref name=WaPoTickTock>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/how-an-outbreak-on-the-uss-roosevelt-became-a-defining-moment-for-the-us-military/2020/04/16/2735f85c-7f24-11ea-8de7-9fdff6d5d83e_story.html How an outbreak on the USS Roosevelt became a defining moment for the U.S. military]. ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 16 April 2020</ref> <ref name = Cohn>{{Cite news |last=Cohn |first=Lindsay |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/05/this-is-what-was-so-unusual-about-us-navy-making-captain-brett-crozier-step-down/ |title=This is what was so unusual about the U.S. Navy making Captain Brett Crozier step down\u2014Members of the military can face multiple, sometimes competing, loyalties |access-date=6 April 2020 |work=The Washington Post |last2=Friend |first2=Alice |last3=Golby |first3=Jim}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, over 100 sailors tested positive.<ref name=Schogol>{{cite web |last1=Schogol |first1=Jeff |title=Navy captain says COVID-19 is spreading through his aircraft carrier so rapidly that most of the crew needs to get off |url=https://taskandpurpose.com/news/uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus-isolation |website=Task & Purpose |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406231152/https://taskandpurpose.com/news/uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus-isolation |archivedate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The letter was leaked to the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]],'' which published it.<ref name = Gafni>{{cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Exclusive-Captain-of-aircraft-carrier-with-15167883.php |title=Exclusive: Captain of aircraft carrier with growing coronavirus outbreak pleads for help from Navy|last1=Gafni|first1=Matthias |last2=Garofoli|first2=Joe |date=31 March 2020|work=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, the Navy ordered the aircraft carrier largely evacuated, with a skeleton crew to remain aboard the vessel to maintain the nuclear reactor, the fire-fighting equipment, the ship's galley, and a disinfection crew.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 >{{cite news|last=Peniston|first=Bradley |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/03/us-navy-evacuating-aircraft-carrier-infected-coronavirus/164254/?oref=d-channelriver |title=US Navy Evacuating Aircraft Carrier Infected by Coronavirus|work=Defense One|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]] relieved Crozier of his command.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> According to Modly, Crozier didn't inform his [[Carrier Strike Group 9|superior on the ship]] about sending the letter, and Modly conferred with Crozier's [[chain of command]].<ref name=Gallagher>{{cite web |last1=Gallagher |first1=Sean |title=Aircraft carrier captain lost his command because of \u201cCatch-22\u201d COVID-19 dilemma |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/04/aircraft-carrier-captain-lost-his-command-because-of-catch-22-covid-19-dilemma/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407231021/https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/04/aircraft-carrier-captain-lost-his-command-because-of-catch-22-covid-19-dilemma/ |archivedate=7 April 2020 |language=en-us |date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, this was not true, because Crozier had sent the letter directly to Rear Admiral Stuart Baker, Commander, [[Carrier Strike Group 9]].<ref name=WaPoTickTock/>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, the Navy confirmed that 155 sailors had been infected and that 1,500 sailors had been removed from the ship, a lower number than the Navy had projected several days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/sailors-uss-teddy-roosevelt-positive-covid-19-navy |title=155 sailors on USS Theodore Roosevelt test positive for coronavirus, 42 percent of all Navy infections |work=Fox News |last=Ruiz |first=Michael |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Modly traveled to Guam to visit the ship in person.<ref name=\"trip\">{{cite news |title=Blistering Reprimand from Navy Secretary |date=7 April 2020 |author=Helene Cooper |work=[[The New York Times]] |page=A11}}</ref> He made a speech to the crew over the ship's [[public address system]], strongly criticizing Crozier. The transcript and an audio recording of Modly's speech were subsequently leaked to the media.<ref name = Larison/> Later that day, Modly apologized for the comment.<ref name = Casiano>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/acting-navy-secretary-uss-theodore-roosevelt-speech-calls-for-his-firing |title=Trump hints that he may get involved in Navy episode as Modly issues apology|last1=Casiano|first1=Louis |last2=Aaro|first2=David |date=7 April 2020|work=Fox News|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> He resigned from his post the following day.\n\nOn 7 April, the Navy said 61% of ''Theodore Roosevelt''{{'}}s crew had been tested for COVID-19 and 173 members had tested positive, including Captain Crozier. None were hospitalized. Two thousand sailors \u2014 just under half the total crew \u2014 had been moved ashore.<ref name=\"Guardian20200407\">{{cite news |last1=Borger|first1=Julian |last2=|first2=|title=US navy official apologises for calling captain behind coronavirus memo 'naive or stupid' |date=7 April 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/06/navy-coronavirus-ship-theodore-roosevelt-thomas-modly |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, the Navy reported that 416 crew members had tested positive for the virus, and that one quarantined sailor was hospitalized in intensive care after being found unconscious in his quarantine quarters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/uss-theodore-roosevelt-sailor-with-coronavirus-taken-to-icu-2020-4 |title=A USS Theodore Roosevelt sailor with coronavirus was taken to the ICU as the number of cases on the aircraft carrier rises|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|date=April 9, 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, it was reported that more than 90% of the crew had been tested for the coronavirus, and 550 crew members had tested positive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/100-new-coronavirus-cases-uss-theodore-roosevelt-550-total-2020-4 |title=100 more sailors from the USS Theodore Roosevelt have tested positive for coronavirus, making up 75% of the Navy's total cases worldwide|last=Holmes|first=Aaron|date=11 April 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=McNamara |first1=Audrey |title=Coronavirus cases on USS Theodore Roosevelt spike to 550|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-cases-on-uss-theodore-roosevelt-spike-to-550-2020-04-11/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=CBS |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 12 April, 585 crew members had tested positive.<ref name = dies/>\n\nOn 13 April, the hospitalized sailor died.<ref name = dies>politico.com: [https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/13/sailor-uss-roosevelt-dies-coronavirus-183164 ''Sailor from USS Theodore Roosevelt dies of coronavirus'']</ref>\n\nAs of 16 April, more than 4,000 of the 4,500 member crew had been removed from the ship.<ref name=WaPoTickTock/> 655 crew members had tested positive. Six were in the hospital<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/493192-fired-captain-sent-memo-to-fewer-people-than-former-navy-head-alleged-report |title=Fired captain sent memo to fewer people than former Navy head alleged: report|last=Kheel|first=Rebecca |date=16 April 2020|work=The Hill|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> including 5 in intensive care. About 60% of the people who tested positive [[asymptomatic|did not have symptoms]].<ref name=phil>{{cite web |author1=Phil Stewart, Idrees Ali |title=Coronavirus clue? Most cases aboard U.S. aircraft carrier are symptom-free |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-military-sympt/coronavirus-clue-most-cases-aboard-u-s-aircraft-carrier-are-symptom-free-idUSKCN21Y2GB |website=[[Reuters]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200417054516/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-military-sympt/coronavirus-clue-most-cases-aboard-u-s-aircraft-carrier-are-symptom-free-idUSKCN21Y2GB |archivedate=17 April 2020 |language=en |date=16 April 2020 |quote=The findings are of enormous interest because the proportion of people who are asymptomatic is just simply not known |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Crozier's letter==\n[[File:Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg|thumb|Ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]]]]\nWhen the ship arrived in Guam on 26 March the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]], wanted to have most of the crew immediately taken ashore, saying it was impossible to prevent the spread of the virus in the close quarters of the ship. Rear Adm. [[Stuart P. Baker]], who was the commanding officer of [[Carrier Strike Group 9]] and thus Crozier's immediate superior, disagreed, feeling such an action was impractical and too drastic.<ref name = losses>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/coronavirus-roosevelt-carrier-crozier.html?campaign_id=60&emc=edit_na_20200413&instance_id=0&nl=breaking-news&ref=cta&regi_id=16153474&segment_id=24971&user_id=e9848bda5d7546386411f6e2fbdaf95e|title=\u2018There Will Be Losses\u2019: How a Captain\u2019s Plea Exposed a Rift in the Military|date=13 April 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Crozier sent an email to communicate the status of his ship and its crew, saying it was not possible to observe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]/Navy<ref>{{cite web |title=Restriction of Movement (ROM) guidance. Navy mitigation measures in response to Novel Coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.public.navy.mil/bupers-npc/reference/messages/Documents/NAVADMINS/NAV2020/NAV20083.txt |publisher=NAVADMIN |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> recommendations for individual quarantine or [[social distancing]] aboard the carrier. Crozier referred to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on Diamond Princess|viral spread on the less crowded cruise ship ''Diamond Princess'']] as an example of [[Basic reproduction number|how quickly a virus can spread]] on a crowded vessel.<ref name = Gafni/><ref name=\"documentcloud\">{{cite web|url=https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/6821571/TR-COVID-19-Assistance-Request.pdf |date=29 March 2020|title=Request for assistance in response to COVID-19 pandemic |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Voltaire>{{cite web |title=Request of assistance in response to pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt, by Captain Brett E. Crozier (text) |url=https://www.voltairenet.org/article209667.html |website=Voltaire Network |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The letter provided his superiors with options, but recommended most<!--90%--> of the crew's evacuation, keeping only enough crew on board to maintain the nuclear reactor, provide security, and to [[Disinfection|sanitize the ship]]. The e-mail was sent to three superior officers in his chain of command, including his direct superior, Rear Admiral Baker, and was copied to seven captains - five of whom were aboard the Roosevent, the other two of whom were executive assistants to the admirals.<ref name=USNI>[https://blog.usni.org/posts/2020/04/17/return-crozier-to-the-roosevelt-restore-faith-in-the-navy Return Crozier to the Roosevelt, Restore Faith in the Navy]. [[Guy Snodgrass]], [[United States Naval Institute]]. April 17, 2020</ref><ref name=WaPoTickTock/><ref name = Cohn/><ref name = losses/> The letter was leaked to the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', which published it the next day.<ref name = Gafni/>\n\n==Relieving Crozier of command and aftermath==\nOn 2 April, acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]] relieved Crozier of his command for sending the request for assistance over non-secure email to a \"broad array of people\" rather than up the chain of command, adding that Crozier \"allowed the complexity of the challenge of the COVID breakout on the ship to overwhelm his ability to act professionally\". Crozier will remain in the Navy and retain his rank.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> As Crozier disembarked, sailors were seen chanting \"Cap-tain Cro-zier\" in a video posted to [[Twitter]] captioned \"Wrongfully relieved of command but did right by the sailors.\"<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[NBC News]] |title=Videos show sailors cheering Navy captain relieved of command after raising alarm on coronavirus |date=3 April 2020 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/videos-show-sailors-cheering-navy-captain-relieved-command-after-raising-n1175946 |first=Janelle |last=Griffith}}</ref>\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?470922-1/us-navy-fires-captain-raised-alarm-coronavirus-aircraft-carrier U.S. Department of Defense briefing with Navy Secretary Modly in which he announces the relief of Capt. Crozier from his duty as the captain of the ''Theodore Roosevelt'', April 2, 2020], [[C-SPAN]]}} Modly claimed that  Crozier had sent a \"blast out email to anybody who he knows about the situation\" and even \"copied [the email] to 20 or 30 other people.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/uss-theodore-roosevelt-commander-fired-after-unclassified-email-2020-4|title='Not acceptable': Navy claims it fired the captain dealing with coronavirus outbreak for sending 'blast out' email to at least 20 people with 'unclassified' system|last=Choi|first=David|date=April 2, 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' subsequently obtained the e-mail and found that it had been sent to only 10 people, all Navy admirals or captains.<ref name=\"WaPoTickTock\"/>\n\nReaction to Crozier's dismissal was mixed. A ''Wall Street Journal'' story reported that on \"Capitol Hill and inside the Pentagon, lawmakers and officials reacted with confusion and anger over the dismissal\" of Crozier.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/captain-fired-by-navy-gets-rousing-farewell-from-sailors-11585933116?mod=hp_lista_pos2 |title=Captain Fired by Navy Gets Rousing Farewell from Sailors |last=Youssef |first=Nancy A. |last2=Lubold |first2=Gordon |date=3 April 2020 |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> A joint statement from four Democrats on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|House Armed Services Committee]], including the committee chair, [[Adam Smith (politician)|Representative Adam Smith (D-WA)]], criticized Crozier's conduct, saying that \"Captain Crozier was justifiably concerned about the health and safety of his crew, but he did not handle the immense pressure appropriately. However, relieving him of his command is an overreaction.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Welna |first1=David |title=After Outcry Over Navy Captain Relieved Of Command, Assurances He Won't Be Expelled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/03/826920834/after-outcry-over-navy-captain-relieved-of-command-assurances-he-wont-be-expelle |website=npr.org |publisher=National Public Radio, Inc.}}</ref> [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] also criticized Crozier's letter on 4 April saying that it was \"not appropriate.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/04/trump-says-navy-captain-letter-asking-for-help-on-coronavirus-stricken-ship-was-terrible.html |title=Trump says Navy captain letter asking for help on coronavirus-stricken ship 'was terrible' |last=Feuer|first=William |date=4 April 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nModly, U.S. Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Michael M. Gilday|Michael Gilday]] each defended the decision to remove Crozier,<ref name=croziergone>{{cite web |first=Rebecca |last=Kheel |title=Aircraft carrier captain removed from duty after pleading for help with coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/490892-aircraft-carrier-captain-to-be-removed-from-duty-after-pleading-for-help-with |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=2020-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Devan |last=Cole |title=Esper defends removing USS Theodore Roosevelt commander who sounded alarm over coronavirus |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/politics/mark-esper-uss-theodore-roosevelt-defends-removal-cnntv/index.html |work=CNN |date=2020-04-05 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> although Gilday and Gen. [[Mark A. Milley]], the [[chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], had earlier advised Modly not to do it until a Navy investigation into the matter had been completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/15/us/politics/coronavirus-navy-roosevelt-crozier.html?campaign_id=9&emc=edit_NN_p_20200416&instance_id=17682&nl=morning-briefing&regi_id=16153474&section=topNews&segment_id=25289&te=1&user_id=e9848bda5d7546386411f6e2fbdaf95e|title=Navy May Reinstate Fired Captain to Command of Roosevelt|date=April 16, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Modly added that there was no White House pressure when the decision was made to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone />\n\nOn 6 April Modly traveled {{convert|8,000|mi}}<ref name=\"trip\"/> to Guam on a Navy executive jet; the trip was later reported to have cost taxpayers at least $243,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2020/04/08/trip-guam-center-top-navy-officials-resignation-cost-taxpayers-least-243000/?utm_campaign=wp_post_most&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&wpisrc=nl_most|title=Trip to Guam at center of top Navy official\u2019s resignation cost taxpayers over $243,000|last=Lamothe|first=Dan|date=April 8, 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> He visited the ship in person and made a speech to the crew over the ship's [[public address system]]. He began by blaming the Chinese government for worsening the outbreak by not telling how bad the disease was. He continued by strongly criticizing Crozier, saying he was \"too na\u00efve or too stupid to be a commanding officer,\" if he did not realize that the letter would be leaked to the media.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ismay |first1=John |last2=Ziezulewicz |first2=Geoff |title=Acting Navy Secretary Slams Fired Captain as 'Stupid' |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/magazine/modly-crozier-coronavirus.html |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Modly also scolded the ship's crew for cheering their captain as he left.<ref name=\"trip\"/>  The transcript and an audio recording of Modly's speech was subsequently leaked to the media.<ref name = Larison>{{cite news |last1=Larison |first1=Daniel |title=After Crozier Comments, Navy Secretary Modly Must Resign |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The American Conservative]] |url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/larison/modly-must-resign/ |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nModly's speech was widely criticized. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Tim Kaine]] stated \"It's deeply disappointing that he would deliver a speech on board a U.S. aircraft carrier suggesting that Captain Crozier might be 'stupid'.\" [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Elaine Luria]] called for the removal of Modly, with Luria, a Navy veteran, saying he was \"in no way fit\" to lead the Navy.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Navy morale dives after firing of virus-riddled ship's captain |url=https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/264591472/us-navy-morale-dives-after-firing-of-virus-riddled-ship-captain |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Big News Network.com |language=en}}</ref> Chairperson of the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Armed Services Committee's panel on military personnel]], [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Jackie Speier]] also criticized the trip.<ref name=\"ModlyCost\">{{cite news |last1=Brook |first1=Tom Vanden |title=Cost of Navy secretary's trip to Guam? $243,000, his job and isolation after coronavirus exposure |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/08/navy-secretary-trip-roosevelt-cost-243-000-leads-modly-ouster/2973486001/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Modly apologized for the comment.<ref name = Casiano/> The following day, he resigned his position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/acting-navy-secretary-resigns-in-wake-of-uss-roosevelt-11586287262 |title=Acting Navy Secretary Thomas Modly Resigns in Wake of USS Roosevelt Comments|last=Lubold|first=Gordon |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\nOn April 13 the first fatality among the sailors from the ship, a 41-year-old chief petty officer, was announced.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5823124/sailor-dies-coronavirus-identified/|title=First Active-Duty Navy Sailor to Die From COVID-19 Is Chief Petty Officer From Stricken Aircraft Carrier|date=16 April 2020|work=Associated Press|publisher=Time Magazine|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> He was the first active-duty member of the U.S. military to die of Covid-19.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-13/navy-sailor-from-uss-theodore-roosevelt-died-of-covid-19 \"Navy Sailor Dies in Guam After Virus Outbreak Aboard Carrier\"] Bloomberg.com</ref>\n\n==Number of confirmed cases==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 15 Apr, 16 Apr, 17 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y1= 3, 8, , , 33, , , , 93, , , , , 155, , 230, 286, 416, 447, 550, 585, 589, 615, 655, 660<!--data missing-->\n|y1Title=Confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|colors=#88aaaaaa,#88436DF4,#88F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|xType=date\n|xAxisFormat=%_d %b\n|showSymbols=1\n|type=stackedarea\n|x= 2020/03/23, 2020/03/24, 2020/03/27, 2020/03/31, 2020/04/05, 2020/04/07, 2020/04/08, 2020/04/09, 2020/04/10, 2020/04/11, 2020/04/12, 2020/04/13, 2020/04/15, 2020/04/16, 2020/04/17\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y3= 3, 8, 33, 93, 155, 230, 286, 416, 447, 550, 585, 589, 615, 655, 660<!--data missing-->\n|y2= ,,,593, 1500, 2037, 2588, 3170, 3284, 3673, 3724, 3922, 3958, 3919, 4059\n|y1= ,,,{{#expr:4865-593-93}},{{#expr:4865-1500-155}},{{#expr:4865-2037-230}},{{#expr:4865-2588-286}},{{#expr:4865-3170-416}},{{#expr:4865-3284-447}},{{#expr:4865-3673-550}},{{#expr:4865-3724-585}},{{#expr:4865-3922-589}}, {{#expr:4865-3958-615}}, {{#expr:4865-3919-655}} , {{#expr:4865-3920-660}}\n|y3Title=Confirmed cases\n|y2Title=Negative cases\n|y1Title=Untested\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania]]\n{{end div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Guam]]\n[[Category:2020 in military history]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by location|USS Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania|USS Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|USS Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Medicine in the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Water transport in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Guam]]\n[[Category:Disasters in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Health and transport]]\n[[Category:Health and military]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n[[Category:Military controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Saschaporsche", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCrozier's letter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_on_USS_Theodore_Roosevelt"}
